1
00:02:55,817 --> 00:02:58,342
Forward march!

2
00:04:30,311 --> 00:04:32,836
I'm requesting-

3
00:04:32,914 --> 00:04:37,044
Captain, I'd like to request
that it be me who's the attorney-

4
00:04:37,118 --> 00:04:39,882
That it be myself who’s assigned.

5
00:04:39,954 --> 00:04:42,787
No, I'd like to request
that it be I who am assigned-

6
00:04:44,358 --> 00:04:46,519
"That it be I who am assigned"?

7
00:04:46,594 --> 00:04:49,927
That's good.
That's confidence-inspiring.

8
00:04:49,997 --> 00:04:51,931
Good grammar there.

9
00:04:51,999 --> 00:04:54,194
Captain, I'd like to request...

10
00:04:54,268 --> 00:04:57,760
that I be the attorney assigned.

11
00:05:00,041 --> 00:05:02,441
I'm Lieutenant Commander Galloway
here to see Captain West.

12
00:05:02,510 --> 00:05:04,444
Go right in, Commander.
They're expecting you.

13
00:05:04,512 --> 00:05:05,945
Thank you.

14
00:05:09,517 --> 00:05:11,451
-Jo, come on in.
- Thank you, sir.

15
00:05:12,587 --> 00:05:15,488
Captain West,
this is Lieutenant Commander Galloway.

16
00:05:15,556 --> 00:05:17,922
-Jo, you know Commander Lawrence.
- Yes, sir.

17
00:05:17,992 --> 00:05:20,153
Captain, I appreciate
you seeing me on such short notice.

18
00:05:20,228 --> 00:05:22,788
- Would you like to sit down?
- I'm fine, sir.

19
00:05:22,864 --> 00:05:25,332
- Have a seat.
- Okay.

20
00:05:25,399 --> 00:05:27,594
I understand we had some trouble
over the weekend down in Cuba?

21
00:05:27,668 --> 00:05:30,967
Yes, sir.
This past Friday, two Marines-

22
00:05:31,038 --> 00:05:34,997
a Lance Corporal Harold Dawson
and a Private Louden Downey-

23
00:05:35,076 --> 00:05:39,274
entered the barracks room of a P.F.C.
William Santiago and assaulted him.

24
00:05:39,347 --> 00:05:42,839
Santiago died at the base hospital
approximately an hour later.

25
00:05:42,917 --> 00:05:46,444
The N.I.S. Agent who took
Dawson and Downey's statements...

26
00:05:46,520 --> 00:05:48,818
maintains they were trying
to prevent Santiago...

27
00:05:48,890 --> 00:05:51,723
from naming Dawson
in a fence line shooting incident.

28
00:05:51,792 --> 00:05:55,558
They're scheduled to have a hearing
down in Cuba this afternoon at 1600.

29
00:05:55,630 --> 00:05:57,564
- What's the problem?
- Dawson and Downey...

30
00:05:57,632 --> 00:06:01,966
are both recruiting poster Marines,
and Santiago was known to be a screw-up.

31
00:06:02,036 --> 00:06:04,800
I was thinking it sounded an awful lot
like a Code Red.

32
00:06:05,606 --> 00:06:07,164
Christ.

33
00:06:07,241 --> 00:06:10,904
Sir, I'd like to have them moved
up to Washington and assigned counsel-

34
00:06:10,978 --> 00:06:13,276
someone who can really
look into this-

35
00:06:13,347 --> 00:06:15,713
someone who possesses
not only the legal skill...

36
00:06:15,783 --> 00:06:18,718
but a familiarity
with the inner workings of the military.

37
00:06:18,786 --> 00:06:21,277
In short, Captain,
I'd like to suggest that...

38
00:06:21,355 --> 00:06:23,323
I be the one who that-

39
00:06:23,391 --> 00:06:27,054
that it be me who is assigned
to represent them...

40
00:06:27,128 --> 00:06:28,561
myself.

41
00:06:30,631 --> 00:06:33,156
Commander Galloway, why don’t you
get yourself a cup of coffee?

42
00:06:33,234 --> 00:06:35,225
Thank you, sir. I'm fine.

43
00:06:35,303 --> 00:06:38,500
I'd like you to leave the room so
we can talk about you behind your back.

44
00:06:38,572 --> 00:06:40,506
Certainly, sir.

45
00:06:47,281 --> 00:06:50,341
I thought this Code Red shit
wasn't going on anymore.

46
00:06:50,418 --> 00:06:53,512
With the Marines at Gitmo, who knows
what the hell goes on down there?

47
00:06:53,587 --> 00:06:55,555
We better find out
before the rest of the world does.

48
00:06:55,623 --> 00:06:57,648
Damn thing could get messy.

49
00:06:57,725 --> 00:07:00,250
All right,
what about this Commander Galloway?

50
00:07:00,328 --> 00:07:03,456
She's been working a desk
in Internal Affairs...

51
00:07:03,531 --> 00:07:05,465
for a little over a year now.

52
00:07:05,533 --> 00:07:08,525
- Before that?
- Disposed of three cases in two years.

53
00:07:08,602 --> 00:07:11,435
Three cases in two years?
Who's she handling, the Rosenbergs?

54
00:07:11,505 --> 00:07:14,030
- She's not cut out for litigation.
- She's a hell of an investigator.

55
00:07:14,108 --> 00:07:17,600
In Internal Affairs she can crawl up
a lawyer's ass with the best of them.

56
00:07:17,678 --> 00:07:21,512
- But when it comes to trial work-
- I know. All passion, no street smarts.

57
00:07:21,582 --> 00:07:23,516
Bring her back in.

58
00:07:33,995 --> 00:07:36,964
Commander, we're gonna have the
defendants moved up here in the morning.

59
00:07:37,031 --> 00:07:40,194
- Thank you, sir.
- Division will assign them counsel.

60
00:07:41,135 --> 00:07:45,629
-But not me.
-From what I get from your colleagues...

61
00:07:45,706 --> 00:07:48,038
you're much too valuable in your
present assignment to be wasted...

62
00:07:48,109 --> 00:07:50,202
in what I'm sure will boil down
to a five-minute plea bargain...

63
00:07:50,277 --> 00:07:52,211
and a week's worth of paperwork.

64
00:07:52,279 --> 00:07:54,406
Sir, I think there might be
more involved than that.

65
00:07:54,482 --> 00:07:55,915
Don't worry about it.

66
00:07:55,983 --> 00:07:58,884
I promise you Division will assign
the right man for the job.

67
00:07:59,320 --> 00:08:01,288
All right. Let's go.
Let's get two.

68
00:08:02,857 --> 00:08:05,052
- Sorry.
- Nothing to be sorry about, Sherby.

69
00:08:05,126 --> 00:08:07,321
You just look the ball
into your glove.

70
00:08:07,395 --> 00:08:08,828
Shooting two.

71
00:08:10,631 --> 00:08:12,599
- Sorry.
- You gotta trust me, Sherby.

72
00:08:12,666 --> 00:08:16,397
Keep your eyes open, your chances of
catching it increase by a factor often.

73
00:08:16,470 --> 00:08:18,335
- Kaffee.
- Let's try it again.

74
00:08:19,507 --> 00:08:21,498
Dave, you seem distraught.

75
00:08:21,575 --> 00:08:24,339
We were supposed to meet 15 minutes ago
about the McDermott case.

76
00:08:24,412 --> 00:08:27,108
You're stalling on this thing.
Now we either do it now...

77
00:08:27,181 --> 00:08:30,776
or, no kidding, Kaffee, I'm gonna
hang your boy from a fucking yardarm!

78
00:08:30,851 --> 00:08:34,810
Yardarm? Sherby, does the Navy
still hang people from yardarms?

79
00:08:34,889 --> 00:08:36,356
I don't think so.

80
00:08:36,424 --> 00:08:39,757
Dave, Sherby doesn't think the Navy
hangs people from yardarms anymore.

81
00:08:39,827 --> 00:08:43,194
I'm gonna charge him with possession
and being under the influence on duty.

82
00:08:43,264 --> 00:08:47,428
You plead guilty, I'll recommend 30 days
in the brig with loss of rank and pay.

83
00:08:47,501 --> 00:08:50,470
It was oregano, Dave.
It was $10 worth of oregano.

84
00:08:50,538 --> 00:08:52,472
Yeah, well, your client thought
it was marijuana.

85
00:08:52,540 --> 00:08:55,270
My client's a moron.
That's not against the law.

86
00:08:55,342 --> 00:08:58,709
Kaffee, I got people to answer to
just like you do. I'm gonna charge him.

87
00:08:58,779 --> 00:09:01,009
With what,
possession of a condiment?

88
00:09:01,082 --> 00:09:03,642
- Kaffee.
- I tried to help you out of this...

89
00:09:03,717 --> 00:09:06,447
but if you ask for jail time,
I'm gonna file a motion to dismiss.

90
00:09:06,520 --> 00:09:08,385
- You won't get it.
- I will get it.

91
00:09:08,456 --> 00:09:10,390
And if the M.T.D. is denied,
I'll file a motion...

92
00:09:10,458 --> 00:09:13,291
seeking to obtain
an evidentiary ruling in advance.

93
00:09:13,360 --> 00:09:15,726
And after that, I'm gonna file
against pretrial confinement.

94
00:09:15,796 --> 00:09:18,321
And you're gonna spend the next three
months going blind on paperwork...

95
00:09:18,399 --> 00:09:22,028
because a signalman second-class bought
and smoked a dime bag of oregano.

96
00:09:22,103 --> 00:09:24,628
Let's go! Let's get two!

97
00:09:25,706 --> 00:09:28,140
B misdemeanor,
20 days in the brig.

98
00:09:28,209 --> 00:09:30,473
C misdemeanor,
15 days restricted duty.

99
00:09:31,946 --> 00:09:33,971
I don't know why
I'm agreeing to this.

100
00:09:34,048 --> 00:09:36,312
'Cause you have wisdom
beyond your years.

101
00:09:40,221 --> 00:09:41,882
Morning.

102
00:09:41,956 --> 00:09:43,651
Morning, Captain.

103
00:09:43,724 --> 00:09:45,248
How's the baby, Sam?

104
00:09:45,326 --> 00:09:48,523
I think she's getting ready
to say her first word any day now.

105
00:09:48,596 --> 00:09:50,188
How can you tell?

106
00:09:50,264 --> 00:09:53,893
She just looks
like she has something to say.

107
00:09:53,968 --> 00:09:56,562
Excuse me.
I'm sorry I'm late.

108
00:09:56,637 --> 00:09:58,628
It's all right, Danny.
I know you don't have a good excuse...

109
00:09:58,706 --> 00:10:00,765
so I won't force you
to come up with a bad one.

110
00:10:00,841 --> 00:10:03,776
- Thank you, sir.
- This first one's for you.

111
00:10:04,845 --> 00:10:07,211
Seems you're moving up
in the world.

112
00:10:07,281 --> 00:10:09,215
Been requested by Division.

113
00:10:10,117 --> 00:10:12,051
Requested to do what?

114
00:10:12,119 --> 00:10:14,485
Guantanamo Bay, Cuba.

115
00:10:14,555 --> 00:10:18,616
A Marine corporal named Dawson illegally
fires a round from his weapon...

116
00:10:18,692 --> 00:10:21,559
over the fence line
and into Cuban territory.

117
00:10:21,629 --> 00:10:23,529
- What's a fence line?
- Sam.

118
00:10:23,597 --> 00:10:27,795
A big wall separating the good guys
from the bad guys.

119
00:10:27,868 --> 00:10:31,133
- Teacher's pet.
- P.F.C. William Santiago...

120
00:10:31,205 --> 00:10:34,538
threatens to rat on Dawson
to Naval Investigative Service.

121
00:10:34,608 --> 00:10:36,633
Dawson and another member
of his squad...

122
00:10:36,710 --> 00:10:40,669
P.F.C. Louden Downey,
go into Santiago's room...

123
00:10:40,748 --> 00:10:44,149
tie him up,
stuff a rag down his throat...

124
00:10:44,218 --> 00:10:46,311
and an hour later, Santiago's dead.

125
00:10:46,387 --> 00:10:50,084
Attending physician says the rag
was treated with some kind of toxin.

126
00:10:50,157 --> 00:10:51,385
They poisoned the rag?

127
00:10:51,458 --> 00:10:54,393
- Not according to them.
- What did they say?

128
00:10:54,461 --> 00:10:57,089
Not much.
They're being flown up here tomorrow...

129
00:10:57,164 --> 00:11:00,622
and on Wednesday at 0600, you'll catch
a transport down to Cuba for the day...

130
00:11:00,701 --> 00:11:02,635
to find out what you can.

131
00:11:02,703 --> 00:11:06,400
Meantime, go and see
Lieutenant Commander Joanne Galloway...

132
00:11:07,942 --> 00:11:09,603
with Internal Affairs.

133
00:11:09,677 --> 00:11:11,201
Any questions?

134
00:11:11,278 --> 00:11:15,305
Uh, the flight to Cuba-
Was that 0600 in the morning, sir?

135
00:11:16,450 --> 00:11:18,850
Seems important to Division
that this one be handled by the book.

136
00:11:18,919 --> 00:11:22,946
So I'm assigning co-counsel.
Any volunteers?

137
00:11:24,647 --> 00:11:25,447
No!

138
00:11:25,626 --> 00:11:27,617
I got a stack of papers on my desk
about a mile high.

139
00:11:27,695 --> 00:11:29,629
- Work with Kaffee on this.
- Doing what?

140
00:11:29,697 --> 00:11:31,927
Kaffee will have this done
in about four days.

141
00:11:31,999 --> 00:11:35,264
Doing various administrative things.

142
00:11:35,336 --> 00:11:37,270
Backup, whatever.

143
00:11:37,338 --> 00:11:39,898
In other words, I have
no responsibilities here whatsoever.

144
00:11:39,974 --> 00:11:41,464
Right.

145
00:11:41,542 --> 00:11:43,635
My kind of case.

146
00:11:44,712 --> 00:11:46,703
Right.

147
00:11:46,780 --> 00:11:49,271
Okay, but I've got to have
that report by Wednesday.

148
00:11:55,656 --> 00:11:58,386
- Hi.
- Hold on. Hi.

149
00:11:58,459 --> 00:12:00,791
Daniel Kaffee.
I was told to me with, uh-

150
00:12:08,702 --> 00:12:11,170
Lieutenant Commander Galloway.

151
00:12:13,407 --> 00:12:14,669
About a briefing?

152
00:12:14,742 --> 00:12:16,676
I'll call you back.

153
00:12:19,413 --> 00:12:21,347
You're the attorney Division assigned?

154
00:12:22,249 --> 00:12:24,183
I'm lead counsel.
This is Sam Weinberg.

155
00:12:24,251 --> 00:12:26,412
I have no responsibilities here
whatsoever.

156
00:12:26,487 --> 00:12:28,648
Come in, please. Have a seat.

157
00:12:39,099 --> 00:12:41,260
Lieutenant, how long
have you been in the Navy?

158
00:12:42,936 --> 00:12:44,870
Going on nine months now.

159
00:12:44,938 --> 00:12:47,532
And how long have you been
out of law school?

160
00:12:48,742 --> 00:12:50,209
A little over a year.

161
00:12:50,277 --> 00:12:52,370
I see.

162
00:12:53,113 --> 00:12:54,705
Have I done something wrong?

163
00:12:54,782 --> 00:12:57,444
No. It’s just that when I petition
Division to have counsel assigned...

164
00:12:57,518 --> 00:12:59,509
I was hoping I'd be taken seriously.

165
00:12:59,586 --> 00:13:02,282
No offense taken,
in case you were wondering.

166
00:13:02,356 --> 00:13:04,221
Commander,
Lieutenant Kaffee is generally...

167
00:13:04,291 --> 00:13:06,657
considered the best litigator
in our office.

168
00:13:06,727 --> 00:13:09,958
He's successfully plea-bargained
44 cases in nine months.

169
00:13:10,030 --> 00:13:12,021
One more,
I get a set of steak knives.

170
00:13:12,099 --> 00:13:13,896
Have you ever been in a courtroom?

171
00:13:13,967 --> 00:13:16,492
I once had
my driver's license suspended.

172
00:13:16,570 --> 00:13:18,538
Commander, from what I understand,
if this thing goes to court...

173
00:13:18,605 --> 00:13:20,766
they won’t need a lawyer,
they'll need a priest.

174
00:13:21,408 --> 00:13:23,342
No, they'll need a lawyer.

175
00:13:24,411 --> 00:13:26,470
Dawson's family's been contacted.

176
00:13:26,547 --> 00:13:30,074
Downey's closest living relative
is Ginny Miller, his aunt.

177
00:13:30,150 --> 00:13:33,051
She hasn't been contacted yet.
Would you like me to take care of that?

178
00:13:33,120 --> 00:13:34,610
Sure. If you feel like it.

179
00:13:36,390 --> 00:13:38,324
One of the people
you'll be seeing down there...

180
00:13:38,392 --> 00:13:40,451
is the barracks C.O.,
Colonel Nathan Jessup.

181
00:13:40,527 --> 00:13:42,654
I assume you’ve heard of him.

182
00:13:42,730 --> 00:13:44,163
Who hasn't?

183
00:13:45,232 --> 00:13:47,826
He's been in the papers lately.
He's expected to be appointed...

184
00:13:47,901 --> 00:13:50,734
director of operations
of National Security Council.

185
00:13:50,804 --> 00:13:52,101
- Really?
- These are the letters...

186
00:13:52,172 --> 00:13:54,470
that Santiago wrote
in his eight months at Gitmo.

187
00:13:54,541 --> 00:13:57,009
- That's Guantanamo Bay.
- I knew that one.

188
00:13:57,077 --> 00:14:00,604
He wrote to the fleet commander
to the commandant of the Marine Corps.

189
00:14:00,681 --> 00:14:03,616
Even his senator. He wanted
to be transferred off the base.

190
00:14:03,684 --> 00:14:05,618
No one was listening.
Are you with me?

191
00:14:05,686 --> 00:14:07,586
Yeah.

192
00:14:08,822 --> 00:14:10,813
Finally, he wrote
to the Naval Investigative Service...

193
00:14:10,891 --> 00:14:13,917
where he offered information about
Corporal Dawson's fence line shooting...

194
00:14:13,994 --> 00:14:16,622
in exchange for a transfer.

195
00:14:16,697 --> 00:14:19,325
Right. Is that all?

196
00:14:19,400 --> 00:14:21,334
Lieutenant,
this letter makes it look like...

197
00:14:21,402 --> 00:14:23,836
your client had a motive
to kill Santiago.

198
00:14:23,904 --> 00:14:27,169
Got you.
And Santiago is who?

199
00:14:27,241 --> 00:14:28,833
The victim.

200
00:14:28,909 --> 00:14:31,537
Write that down.
Am I correct to assume these letters...

201
00:14:31,612 --> 00:14:34,513
don't paint a flattering picture
of Marine Corps life at Guantanamo Bay?

202
00:14:34,581 --> 00:14:36,048
- Yes, among-
- Am I further right in assuming...

203
00:14:36,116 --> 00:14:39,950
investigation of this incident might
embarrass the Security Council guy?

204
00:14:40,020 --> 00:14:42,011
- Colonel Jessup.
- Twelve years.

205
00:14:43,090 --> 00:14:44,022
Sorry?

206
00:14:44,091 --> 00:14:46,286
I'll get them to drop the conspiracy
and conduct unbecoming.

207
00:14:46,360 --> 00:14:48,123
Twelve years.

208
00:14:48,195 --> 00:14:51,824
You haven't talked to a witness
or looked at a piece of paper.

209
00:14:51,899 --> 00:14:53,958
Pretty impressive, huh?

210
00:14:54,034 --> 00:14:55,729
You're gonna have
to go deeper than that.

211
00:14:55,803 --> 00:14:58,567
Do you have some sort of jurisdiction
here that I should know about?

212
00:14:58,639 --> 00:15:01,437
My job is to make sure
that you do your job.

213
00:15:01,508 --> 00:15:03,476
I'm special counsel
for Internal Affairs...

214
00:15:03,544 --> 00:15:06,911
so my jurisdiction’s pretty much
in your face.

215
00:15:09,082 --> 00:15:12,142
Read the letters. I'll expect
your report when you return from Cuba.

216
00:15:12,219 --> 00:15:14,881
- Sure.
- You're dismissed.

217
00:15:17,157 --> 00:15:19,489
I always forget that part.

218
00:15:21,261 --> 00:15:24,025
He's a little preoccupied.

219
00:15:24,097 --> 00:15:27,260
Team's playing Bethesda Medical
next week.

220
00:15:27,334 --> 00:15:29,268
Tell your friend
not to get cute down there.

221
00:15:29,336 --> 00:15:31,668
The Marines in Guantanamo
are fanatical.

222
00:15:31,738 --> 00:15:33,035
About what?

223
00:15:33,774 --> 00:15:35,435
About being Marines.

224
00:15:35,509 --> 00:15:36,533
Dear sir...

225
00:15:36,610 --> 00:15:39,374
my name is P.F.C. William T. Santiago.

226
00:15:39,446 --> 00:15:41,778
I'm a Marine stationed
at Marine barracks...

227
00:15:41,849 --> 00:15:45,046
Rifle Security Company Windward,
Second Platoon Bravo.

228
00:15:45,118 --> 00:15:48,918
I'm writing to inform you of my problems
with my unit here in Cuba...

229
00:15:48,989 --> 00:15:50,616
and to ask for your help.

230
00:15:50,691 --> 00:15:54,024
I've fallen out on runs before
for several reasons...

231
00:15:54,094 --> 00:15:56,062
such as feeling dizzy or nauseated.

232
00:15:56,129 --> 00:15:59,860
But on May 18, I'd fallen back
about 20 or 30 yards...

233
00:15:59,933 --> 00:16:02,458
going down rocky unstable hill.

234
00:16:02,536 --> 00:16:05,505
My sergeant grabbed me
and pushed me down the hill.

235
00:16:05,572 --> 00:16:09,474
Then I saw all black, and the last thing
I remembered was hitting the deck.

236
00:16:09,543 --> 00:16:12,910
I was brought to the hospital where
I was told I just had heat exhaustion.

237
00:16:12,980 --> 00:16:14,607
I ask you to help me.

238
00:16:14,681 --> 00:16:18,139
Please, sir. I just need
to be transferred out of R.S.C.

239
00:16:18,218 --> 00:16:21,051
Sincerely,
P.F.C. William T. Santiago...

240
00:16:21,121 --> 00:16:22,713
U.S. Marine Corps.

241
00:16:22,789 --> 00:16:25,724
P.S. In exchange for my transfer
off the base...

242
00:16:25,792 --> 00:16:27,783
I'm willing to provide you
with information about-

243
00:16:27,861 --> 00:16:32,127
"The illegal fence line shooting
that occurred the night of August 2."

244
00:16:33,066 --> 00:16:37,435
Who the fuck
is P.F.C. William T. Santiago?

245
00:16:37,504 --> 00:16:40,598
Private Santiago is a member
of Second Platoon Bravo, sir.

246
00:16:40,674 --> 00:16:44,872
Yeah. Well, apparently he's not
very happy down here in Shangri-la...

247
00:16:44,945 --> 00:16:47,812
because he's written letters
to everybody but Santa Claus...

248
00:16:47,881 --> 00:16:50,008
asking for a transfer.

249
00:16:50,083 --> 00:16:53,018
And now he's telling tales
about a fence line shooting.

250
00:16:54,087 --> 00:16:55,679
Matthew?

251
00:16:55,756 --> 00:16:58,316
I'm appalled, sir.

252
00:16:59,126 --> 00:17:01,560
You're appalled.

253
00:17:02,629 --> 00:17:06,156
This kid broke the chain of command
and ratted on a member of his unit...

254
00:17:06,233 --> 00:17:09,031
to say nothing of the fact
that he is a U.S. Marine...

255
00:17:09,102 --> 00:17:11,832
and it would appear he can't run
from here to there...

256
00:17:11,905 --> 00:17:14,669
without collapsing
from heat exhaustion.

257
00:17:14,741 --> 00:17:18,006
What the fuck is going on
in Bravo Company, Matthew?

258
00:17:18,078 --> 00:17:21,104
Colonel, I think it would be better
to hold this discussion in private.

259
00:17:21,181 --> 00:17:25,311
That won't be necessary, Colonel.
I can handle the situation, sir.

260
00:17:25,385 --> 00:17:29,116
The same way you handled Curtis Bell?
Don't interrupt me, Lieutenant!

261
00:17:29,189 --> 00:17:32,716
- I'm still your superior officer.
- And I'm yours, Matthew.

262
00:17:34,895 --> 00:17:37,955
I wanna know
what we're going to do about this.

263
00:17:38,031 --> 00:17:40,966
I think Santiago should be transferred
off the base immediately.

264
00:17:41,034 --> 00:17:42,661
He's that bad, huh?

265
00:17:42,736 --> 00:17:44,863
Not only that. But word
of this letter is bound to get out.

266
00:17:44,938 --> 00:17:46,872
He's gonna get his ass whipped.

267
00:17:46,940 --> 00:17:50,967
Hmm. Transfer Santiago.

268
00:17:51,044 --> 00:17:54,571
Yes. I'm sure you’re right.

269
00:17:54,648 --> 00:17:57,139
I'm sure that's the thing to do.

270
00:17:58,852 --> 00:18:02,754
Wait. I've got a better idea.

271
00:18:02,823 --> 00:18:05,758
Let's transfer the whole squad
off the base.

272
00:18:05,826 --> 00:18:08,920
Let's- On second thought, Windward-

273
00:18:08,996 --> 00:18:13,228
Let's transfer the whole
Windward Division off the base.

274
00:18:13,300 --> 00:18:16,929
John, go on out there
and get those boys down off the fence.

275
00:18:17,004 --> 00:18:19,495
They're packing their bags. Tom.

276
00:18:20,774 --> 00:18:23,174
- Sir.
- Get me the president on the phone.

277
00:18:23,243 --> 00:18:26,337
We're surrendering
our position in Cuba.

278
00:18:26,413 --> 00:18:28,847
- Yes, sir.
- Wait a minute, Tom.

279
00:18:28,915 --> 00:18:30,849
Don't get the president just yet.

280
00:18:30,917 --> 00:18:34,546
Maybe we should
consider this for a second.

281
00:18:34,621 --> 00:18:36,885
- Dismissed, Tom.
- Yes, sir.

282
00:18:37,991 --> 00:18:41,859
Maybe- and I'm just
spit-balling here-

283
00:18:41,928 --> 00:18:46,956
Maybe we have a responsibility
as officers to train Santiago.

284
00:18:47,034 --> 00:18:51,198
Maybe we as officers
have a responsibility to this country...

285
00:18:51,271 --> 00:18:54,570
to see that the men and women
charged with its security...

286
00:18:54,641 --> 00:18:56,700
are trained professionals.

287
00:18:56,777 --> 00:19:00,713
Yes, I'm certain
that I read that somewhere once.

288
00:19:00,781 --> 00:19:03,375
And now I'm thinking,
Colonel Markinson...

289
00:19:03,450 --> 00:19:07,784
that your suggestion
of transferring Santiago...

290
00:19:07,854 --> 00:19:11,085
while expeditious
and certainly painless...

291
00:19:11,158 --> 00:19:13,649
might not be,
in a manner of speaking...

292
00:19:13,727 --> 00:19:16,628
the American way.

293
00:19:16,697 --> 00:19:19,495
Santiago stays where he is.

294
00:19:21,201 --> 00:19:23,533
We're gonna train the lad.

295
00:19:23,603 --> 00:19:26,538
John, you're in charge.

296
00:19:26,606 --> 00:19:29,769
Santiago doesn't make 4-6-4-6...

297
00:19:29,843 --> 00:19:33,506
on his next proficiency
and conduct report...

298
00:19:33,580 --> 00:19:35,912
I'm going to blame you.

299
00:19:35,982 --> 00:19:38,610
- Then I'm going to kill you.
- Yes, sir.

300
00:19:38,685 --> 00:19:41,279
I think that's a mistake, Colonel.

301
00:19:42,689 --> 00:19:46,819
Matthew, I think I will
have that word in private with you now.

302
00:19:46,893 --> 00:19:50,852
John, that's all. Why don't we meet
at the "O" club and have lunch...

303
00:19:50,931 --> 00:19:53,525
and we'll talk about the training
of young William?

304
00:19:53,600 --> 00:19:56,330
I'd be delighted to hear any
suggestions that you might have, sir.

305
00:19:56,403 --> 00:19:58,371
- Dismissed.
- Yes, sir.

306
00:20:02,142 --> 00:20:05,339
Matthew, sit down. Please.

307
00:20:10,517 --> 00:20:13,111
What do you think of Kendrick?

308
00:20:13,186 --> 00:20:15,017
My opinion of him has nothing to do-

309
00:20:15,088 --> 00:20:18,251
I think he's pretty much
of a weasel myself...

310
00:20:18,325 --> 00:20:20,316
but he's an awfully good officer.

311
00:20:20,393 --> 00:20:24,830
And in the end, we see eye-to-eye on
the best way to run a Marine Corps unit.

312
00:20:24,898 --> 00:20:28,425
We're in the business
of saving lives, Matthew.

313
00:20:28,502 --> 00:20:32,199
That is a responsibility
that we have to take pretty seriously.

314
00:20:32,272 --> 00:20:36,606
And I believe that taking a Marine
who is not quite up to the job...

315
00:20:36,676 --> 00:20:39,144
and shipping him off
to another assignment...

316
00:20:39,212 --> 00:20:41,203
puts lives in danger.

317
00:20:41,982 --> 00:20:44,246
Sit down, Matthew.

318
00:20:53,760 --> 00:20:55,819
We go back a while.

319
00:20:55,896 --> 00:20:59,388
We went to the Academy together.
We were commissioned together.

320
00:20:59,466 --> 00:21:01,934
We did our tours in Vietnam together.

321
00:21:02,002 --> 00:21:04,368
But I've been promoted
up through the chain...

322
00:21:04,437 --> 00:21:07,338
with greater speed and success
than you have.

323
00:21:07,407 --> 00:21:10,376
Now, if that’s a source of tension...

324
00:21:10,443 --> 00:21:12,411
or embarrassment for you...

325
00:21:12,479 --> 00:21:14,242
I don't give a shit.

326
00:21:14,314 --> 00:21:19,513
We're in the business of saving lives,
Lieutenant Colonel Markinson.

327
00:21:19,586 --> 00:21:23,682
Don't ever question my orders
in front of another officer.

328
00:21:43,677 --> 00:21:45,144
All the paperwork's in order.

329
00:21:46,213 --> 00:21:48,147
- Step over there.
- Yes, sir.

330
00:21:52,819 --> 00:21:55,583
Hal, is this Washington, D.C.?

331
00:21:55,655 --> 00:21:57,282
All right. Let's move.

332
00:21:57,357 --> 00:21:58,790
Yes, sir.

333
00:22:05,665 --> 00:22:08,600
- Got all of that one.
- Excuse me.

334
00:22:08,668 --> 00:22:12,263
I wanted to talk to you about
Corporal Dawson and Private Downey.

335
00:22:12,339 --> 00:22:14,933
- Say again?
- Dawson and Downey.

336
00:22:16,209 --> 00:22:18,234
Those names sound like
they should mean something to me-

337
00:22:18,311 --> 00:22:21,109
Dawson, Downey - your clients.

338
00:22:21,181 --> 00:22:24,480
The Cuba thing. Yes!
Dawson and Downey. Right.

339
00:22:27,687 --> 00:22:29,746
I've done something wrong again,
haven't I?

340
00:22:29,823 --> 00:22:31,814
I was just wondering
why two guys have been locked up...

341
00:22:31,892 --> 00:22:34,656
since this morning while their lawyer's
outside hitting a ball.

342
00:22:36,663 --> 00:22:38,358
We need the practice.

343
00:22:38,431 --> 00:22:40,023
That wasn't funny.

344
00:22:40,767 --> 00:22:42,132
It was a little funny.

345
00:22:42,202 --> 00:22:45,501
Would you be very insulted
if I recommended to your supervisor...

346
00:22:45,572 --> 00:22:47,506
that he assign different counsel?

347
00:22:47,574 --> 00:22:51,010
- Why?
- I don't think you’re fit to handle it.

348
00:22:51,077 --> 00:22:54,843
You don't even know me.
Ordinarily, it takes someone hours...

349
00:22:54,915 --> 00:22:57,543
to discover I'm not fit
to handle a defense.

350
00:22:59,286 --> 00:23:02,653
Oh, come on.
That was damn funny.

351
00:23:05,659 --> 00:23:06,819
You're wrong.

352
00:23:07,894 --> 00:23:09,885
I do know you.

353
00:23:09,963 --> 00:23:13,797
Daniel Alistair Kaffee,
born June 8, 1964...

354
00:23:13,867 --> 00:23:15,801
at Boston Mercy Hospital.

355
00:23:15,869 --> 00:23:17,200
Your father's Lionel Kaffee...

356
00:23:17,270 --> 00:23:20,762
former Navy judge advocate and
attorney general of the United States.

357
00:23:20,840 --> 00:23:22,398
Died 1985.

358
00:23:22,475 --> 00:23:25,205
You went to Harvard law.
Then you joined the Navy...

359
00:23:25,278 --> 00:23:28,042
probably because that's
what your father wanted you to do.

360
00:23:28,114 --> 00:23:31,447
And now you're just treading water
for three years in the JAG Corps.

361
00:23:31,518 --> 00:23:35,010
Just laying low till
you can get out and get a real job.

362
00:23:35,088 --> 00:23:38,649
If that’s the situation, that's fine.
I won't tell anyone.

363
00:23:38,725 --> 00:23:41,023
But it's my feeling that
if this case is handled in the same...

364
00:23:41,094 --> 00:23:43,961
fast-food, slick-ass,
Persian bazaar manner...

365
00:23:44,030 --> 00:23:45,964
with which you seem
to handle everything else...

366
00:23:46,032 --> 00:23:47,693
then something's gonna get missed.

367
00:23:47,767 --> 00:23:50,429
And I wouldn't be doing my job
if I allowed Dawson and Downey...

368
00:23:50,503 --> 00:23:53,063
to spend any more time in prison
than absolutely necessary...

369
00:23:53,139 --> 00:23:56,233
because their attorney had predetermined
the path of least resistance.

370
00:23:59,012 --> 00:24:00,445
Wow.

371
00:24:01,581 --> 00:24:04,049
I'm sexually aroused, Commander.

372
00:24:04,751 --> 00:24:07,015
I don't think
your clients murdered anyone.

373
00:24:07,087 --> 00:24:08,452
What are you basing this on?

374
00:24:08,521 --> 00:24:10,318
There was no intent.

375
00:24:10,390 --> 00:24:13,223
The doctor's report says
Santiago died of asphyxiation...

376
00:24:13,293 --> 00:24:15,227
brought on by acute lactic acidosis...

377
00:24:15,295 --> 00:24:19,129
and that the nature of the acidosis
strongly suggests poison.

378
00:24:19,199 --> 00:24:21,963
I don't know what any of that means,
but it sounds pretty bad.

379
00:24:22,035 --> 00:24:23,969
Santiago died at 1:00 a. m.

380
00:24:24,037 --> 00:24:26,835
At 3:00, the doctor wasn’t able
to determine the cause of death.

381
00:24:26,906 --> 00:24:29,136
Two hours later,
he said it was poison.

382
00:24:29,209 --> 00:24:31,734
Oh, now I see what you’re saying.

383
00:24:31,811 --> 00:24:35,110
It had to be Professor Plum
in the library with a candlestick.

384
00:24:35,181 --> 00:24:37,649
- I'm gonna talk to your supervisor.
- Okay.

385
00:24:37,717 --> 00:24:39,878
Go straight up Pennsylvania Avenue.

386
00:24:39,953 --> 00:24:42,444
It's the big white house
with the pillars in front.

387
00:24:42,522 --> 00:24:45,719
- Thank you.
- I don't think you’ll have much luck.

388
00:24:45,792 --> 00:24:47,225
I was assigned by Division.

389
00:24:47,293 --> 00:24:50,353
Somebody over there thinks
I'm a pretty good lawyer.

390
00:24:50,430 --> 00:24:53,922
So while I appreciate your interest
and admire your enthusiasm...

391
00:24:54,000 --> 00:24:56,468
I think I can handle things myself.

392
00:24:56,536 --> 00:24:58,629
You know what a Code Red is?

393
00:25:02,509 --> 00:25:04,636
What a pity.

394
00:25:14,854 --> 00:25:17,322
- Morning, sir.
- Morning.

395
00:25:18,258 --> 00:25:19,919
Officer on deck!

396
00:25:19,993 --> 00:25:22,154
Sir, Lance Corporal
Harold W. Dawson, sir!

397
00:25:22,228 --> 00:25:24,423
Rifle Security Company Windward,
Second Platoon Bravo.

398
00:25:24,497 --> 00:25:27,762
Someone hasn't been working
and playing well with others, Harold.

399
00:25:27,834 --> 00:25:29,768
Sir, yes, sir!

400
00:25:31,538 --> 00:25:33,870
Sir, P.F.C. Louden Downey, sir!

401
00:25:35,375 --> 00:25:37,969
I'm Daniel Kaffee.
This is Sam Weinberg.

402
00:25:38,044 --> 00:25:39,204
Sit down.

403
00:25:46,519 --> 00:25:49,317
- This your signature?
- Yes, sir.

404
00:25:49,389 --> 00:25:51,186
You don't have to call me "sir. "
Is this your signature?

405
00:25:51,257 --> 00:25:52,451
Sir, yes, sir.

406
00:25:52,525 --> 00:25:55,392
You certainly don't need
to do it twice in one sentence.

407
00:25:55,462 --> 00:25:59,057
- What's a Code Red?
- It is a disciplinary engagement.

408
00:25:59,132 --> 00:26:00,565
What's that mean?

409
00:26:00,633 --> 00:26:04,501
A Marine falls out of line, it's up to
the men in his unit to get him on track.

410
00:26:04,571 --> 00:26:08,063
- What's a garden variety Code Red?
- Sir?

411
00:26:08,141 --> 00:26:12,077
Harold, you say, "sir," and
I turn around and look for my father.

412
00:26:12,145 --> 00:26:14,705
Danny, Daniel, Kaffee.

413
00:26:14,781 --> 00:26:17,841
Garden variety. Typical.
What's basic Code Red?

414
00:26:17,917 --> 00:26:20,545
Sir, a Marine refuses to bathe
on a regular basis...

415
00:26:20,620 --> 00:26:23,214
the men in his squad
will give him a G.I. shower.

416
00:26:23,289 --> 00:26:24,551
What's that?

417
00:26:24,624 --> 00:26:27,149
Scrub brushes,
Brillo pads, steel wool.

418
00:26:27,227 --> 00:26:28,558
Beautiful.

419
00:26:28,628 --> 00:26:31,153
Was the attack on Santiago
a Code Red?

420
00:26:31,231 --> 00:26:32,926
Yes, sir.

421
00:26:38,171 --> 00:26:41,334
Does he ever talk?

422
00:26:41,407 --> 00:26:44,706
Sir, P.F.C. Downey will answer
any direct questions you ask him.

423
00:26:44,777 --> 00:26:46,335
Swell.

424
00:26:47,947 --> 00:26:50,711
Private Downey, the rag
you stuffed in Santiago's mouth-

425
00:26:50,783 --> 00:26:52,717
- Was there poison on it?
- No, sir.

426
00:26:52,785 --> 00:26:55,276
Silver polish,
turpentine, antifreeze?

427
00:26:55,355 --> 00:26:57,721
No, sir. We were just
gonna shave his head, sir.

428
00:26:57,790 --> 00:27:00,588
When all of the sudden-

429
00:27:00,660 --> 00:27:03,094
We saw blood dripping
down his mouth...

430
00:27:03,163 --> 00:27:07,361
and we pulled the tape off and
there was blood all down his face, sir.

431
00:27:07,433 --> 00:27:10,698
That's when Lance Corporal Dawson
called the ambulance.

432
00:27:10,770 --> 00:27:12,465
Did anyone see you call
the ambulance?

433
00:27:14,474 --> 00:27:15,634
No, sir.

434
00:27:18,144 --> 00:27:19,873
Were you there
when the ambulance got there?

435
00:27:19,946 --> 00:27:22,312
Yes, sir. That's when
we were taken under arrest.

436
00:27:22,382 --> 00:27:27,183
The night of August 2, did you fire
a shot across the fence line into Cuba?

437
00:27:29,122 --> 00:27:30,555
- Yes, sir.
- Why?

438
00:27:30,623 --> 00:27:33,421
- My mirror engaged, sir.
- His mirror?

439
00:27:33,493 --> 00:27:37,361
Every American sentry post has
a Cuban counterpart, called "mirrors. "

440
00:27:37,430 --> 00:27:40,888
Lance Corporal's claiming that
his mirror was about to fire at him.

441
00:27:40,967 --> 00:27:43,435
Santiago's letter to the N.I.S...

442
00:27:43,503 --> 00:27:45,971
said you fired illegally.

443
00:27:46,039 --> 00:27:49,975
He's saying that the guy, the mirror-

444
00:27:50,043 --> 00:27:51,635
He never made a move.

445
00:27:58,084 --> 00:28:00,018
You see what I'm getting at?

446
00:28:01,087 --> 00:28:04,318
If Santiago didn't have anything on you,
then why did you give him a Code Red?

447
00:28:04,390 --> 00:28:06,585
'Cause he broke
the chain of command, sir.

448
00:28:06,659 --> 00:28:09,628
- He what?
- He went outside of his unit, sir.

449
00:28:09,696 --> 00:28:12,096
If he had a problem,
he should have spoken to me, sir.

450
00:28:12,165 --> 00:28:15,191
- Then his sergeant, then commander-
- Yeah. All right.

451
00:28:15,268 --> 00:28:17,930
Did you assault Santiago
with the intent of killing him?

452
00:28:18,004 --> 00:28:19,665
- No, sir.
- What was your intent?

453
00:28:19,739 --> 00:28:22,503
- To train him, sir.
- Train him to do what?

454
00:28:22,575 --> 00:28:27,103
Train him to think of his unit
before himself- to respect the code.

455
00:28:27,180 --> 00:28:28,977
What's the code?

456
00:28:29,048 --> 00:28:31,016
Unit, Corps, God, Country.

457
00:28:31,084 --> 00:28:32,346
I beg your pardon?

458
00:28:32,418 --> 00:28:37,788
Unit, Corps, God, Country, sir.

459
00:28:53,673 --> 00:28:56,574
The government
of the United States...

460
00:28:56,643 --> 00:28:59,441
wants to charge you two
with murder...

461
00:28:59,512 --> 00:29:01,503
and you want me
to go to the prosecutor...

462
00:29:01,581 --> 00:29:05,142
with "Unit, Corps, God, Country"?

463
00:29:05,218 --> 00:29:07,209
That's our code, sir.

464
00:29:11,224 --> 00:29:13,055
It's your code.

465
00:29:13,126 --> 00:29:15,686
We'll be back.

466
00:29:15,762 --> 00:29:19,630
You guys need anything- books,
papers, cigarettes, ham sandwich?

467
00:29:19,699 --> 00:29:21,997
Sir, no, thank you, sir.

468
00:29:22,068 --> 00:29:25,868
Harold, I think there's a concept
you better start warming up to.

469
00:29:25,938 --> 00:29:27,200
Sir?

470
00:29:27,273 --> 00:29:29,867
I'm the only friend you've got.

471
00:29:45,024 --> 00:29:46,286
Smiling Jack Ross.

472
00:29:46,359 --> 00:29:48,589
- Welcome to the big time.
- You think so?

473
00:29:48,661 --> 00:29:52,529
Let's hope, for Dawson and Downey, you
practice law better than play softball.

474
00:29:52,598 --> 00:29:56,125
Unfortunately for those two, I don't
do anything better than play softball.

475
00:29:56,202 --> 00:29:57,726
- I'm out of here, Janelle.
- Bye.

476
00:29:57,804 --> 00:30:00,102
- See you when I get back from Cuba.
- Say hi to Castro for me.

477
00:30:00,173 --> 00:30:02,471
Will do.
What are we looking at?

478
00:30:02,542 --> 00:30:05,705
They plead guilty, we drop
the conspiracy and conduct unbecoming.

479
00:30:05,778 --> 00:30:08,042
- Twenty years. They're home in half.
- I want 12.

480
00:30:08,114 --> 00:30:10,082
- Can't do it.
- They called the ambulance.

481
00:30:10,149 --> 00:30:13,482
I don't care if they called
the Avon lady. They killed a Marine.

482
00:30:13,553 --> 00:30:15,953
The rag was tested for poison.
The autopsy, lab reports.

483
00:30:16,022 --> 00:30:17,683
They say the same thing:
maybe, maybe not.

484
00:30:17,757 --> 00:30:20,817
Chief of Internal Medicine
at the Guantanamo Bay Naval Hospital...

485
00:30:20,893 --> 00:30:22,417
says he's sure.

486
00:30:22,495 --> 00:30:24,554
What do you know about Code Reds?

487
00:30:24,630 --> 00:30:26,063
Oh, man.

488
00:30:28,568 --> 00:30:31,059
- We off the record?
- Tell me.

489
00:30:32,338 --> 00:30:34,272
I'm gonna give you the 12 years.

490
00:30:34,340 --> 00:30:37,503
Before you go getting yourself into
trouble tomorrow, you should know...

491
00:30:37,577 --> 00:30:39,704
the platoon commander,
Lieutenant Jonathan Kendrick...

492
00:30:39,779 --> 00:30:42,714
held a meeting with the men
and specifically...

493
00:30:42,782 --> 00:30:45,216
told them not to touch Santiago.

494
00:30:47,820 --> 00:30:50,653
- We still playing hoops tomorrow night?
- Do we have a deal?

495
00:30:50,723 --> 00:30:53,419
I'll talk to you when I get back.

496
00:30:56,896 --> 00:30:59,660
- Hi there.
- Any luck getting me replaced?

497
00:30:59,732 --> 00:31:02,963
Is there anyone in this command you
don't either drink or play ball with?

498
00:31:03,035 --> 00:31:04,969
- Commander-
- Listen. I came to make peace.

499
00:31:05,037 --> 00:31:09,064
Got off on the wrong foot.
What do you say? Friends?

500
00:31:09,142 --> 00:31:12,202
I brought Downey some comic books
he was asking for.

501
00:31:12,278 --> 00:31:14,712
The kid, Kaffee,
I swear he doesn't know where he is.

502
00:31:14,781 --> 00:31:17,113
- Doesn't even know why he's arrested.
- Commander.

503
00:31:17,183 --> 00:31:18,946
- You can call me Joanne.
-Joanne.

504
00:31:19,018 --> 00:31:21,248
- Or Jo.
- Yes.

505
00:31:21,320 --> 00:31:24,312
Jo, if you ever speak to a client
of mine again without my permission...

506
00:31:24,390 --> 00:31:25,948
I'll have you disbarred.

507
00:31:26,025 --> 00:31:29,256
- Friends?
- I had authorization.

508
00:31:29,328 --> 00:31:32,092
- From where?
- Downey's closest living relative.

509
00:31:32,165 --> 00:31:35,726
Ginny Miller.
His aunt on his mother's side.

510
00:31:35,802 --> 00:31:38,134
You got authorization
from Aunt Ginny?

511
00:31:38,204 --> 00:31:40,195
I gave her a call
like you asked.

512
00:31:40,273 --> 00:31:42,673
Very nice woman.
We spoke for about an hour.

513
00:31:42,742 --> 00:31:45,267
You got authorization
from Aunt Ginny.

514
00:31:45,344 --> 00:31:48,006
Perfectly within my province.

515
00:31:48,080 --> 00:31:50,514
Does Aunt Ginny have a barn?
We could hold the trial there.

516
00:31:50,583 --> 00:31:53,711
I can sew the costumes.
Maybe his Uncle Goober can be the judge.

517
00:31:57,156 --> 00:31:59,681
I'm going to Cuba with you tomorrow.

518
00:32:01,694 --> 00:32:04,492
And the hits just keep on coming.

519
00:32:27,520 --> 00:32:31,081
- How's it going, Luther?
- Another day, another dollar, captain.

520
00:32:31,157 --> 00:32:34,354
- You gotta play them as they lay.
- What goes around comes around.

521
00:32:34,427 --> 00:32:37,863
- Can't beat 'em, join 'em.
- At least I got my health.

522
00:32:37,930 --> 00:32:41,696
Well, then you got everything.
See you tomorrow, Luther.

523
00:32:41,767 --> 00:32:43,701
Not if I see you first.

524
00:32:46,038 --> 00:32:48,029
Now don't forget.
When Sally gets back, you're my witness.

525
00:32:48,107 --> 00:32:50,405
The baby spoke.
My daughter said a word.

526
00:32:50,476 --> 00:32:52,774
Your daughter made a sound, Sam.
I'm not sure it was a word.

527
00:32:52,845 --> 00:32:54,779
Come on, now.
It was definitely a word.

528
00:32:57,683 --> 00:33:00,345
You heard her. The girl sat here,
pointed and said, " Pa. "

529
00:33:00,419 --> 00:33:02,512
She did. She said, " Pa. "

530
00:33:02,588 --> 00:33:04,818
She was pointing at a mailbox, Sam.

531
00:33:04,891 --> 00:33:08,850
That's right, pointing as if to say,
" Pa, look. A mailbox. "

532
00:33:16,402 --> 00:33:19,530
Jack Ross came to see me today.
He offered me the 12 years.

533
00:33:19,605 --> 00:33:22,301
- Oh, that's what you wanted, right?
- I know, I know.

534
00:33:23,376 --> 00:33:27,938
I mean, I guess I'll take it.
I'll take it.

535
00:33:29,015 --> 00:33:32,143
- So-
- It took about 45 seconds.

536
00:33:32,218 --> 00:33:33,913
He barely put up a fight.

537
00:33:33,986 --> 00:33:36,546
Danny, take the 12 years.
It's a gift.

538
00:33:37,623 --> 00:33:39,557
You don't believe their story,
do you?

539
00:33:39,625 --> 00:33:41,786
You think they ought to go to jail
for the rest of their lives.

540
00:33:41,861 --> 00:33:44,056
I believe every word of their story...

541
00:33:44,130 --> 00:33:47,156
and I think they ought to go to jail
for the rest of their lives.

542
00:33:52,605 --> 00:33:54,539
- See you tomorrow.
- Okay.

543
00:33:54,607 --> 00:33:57,235
Don't forget to wear the whites.
Very hot down there.

544
00:33:57,310 --> 00:33:59,175
I don't like the whites.

545
00:33:59,245 --> 00:34:01,611
Nobody likes the whites,
but we're going to Cuba.

546
00:34:01,681 --> 00:34:04,377
- You got Dramamine?
- Dramamine keeps you cool?

547
00:34:04,450 --> 00:34:08,011
No, Dramamine keeps you from
throwing up. You get sick when you fly.

548
00:34:08,087 --> 00:34:11,454
I get sick when I fly because I'm afraid
of crashing into a large mountain.

549
00:34:11,524 --> 00:34:13,082
I don't think Dramamine will help.

550
00:34:14,093 --> 00:34:16,527
I got some oregano.
I hear that works pretty good.

551
00:34:19,966 --> 00:34:23,197
You know, Ross said the strangest thing
to me right before I left.

552
00:34:23,269 --> 00:34:26,670
He said the platoon commander
Lieutenant Jonathan Kendrick...

553
00:34:26,739 --> 00:34:30,368
had a meeting with the men
and told them not to touch Santiago.

554
00:34:30,443 --> 00:34:31,842
So?

555
00:34:33,212 --> 00:34:35,578
I never mentioned Kendrick.
I don't even know who he is.

556
00:34:39,218 --> 00:34:43,211
Ah, what the hell.
I'll see you tomorrow.

557
00:35:19,125 --> 00:35:21,821
Lieutenants Kaffee and Weinberg,
Commander Galloway.

558
00:35:21,894 --> 00:35:24,590
I'm Corporal Barnes. I'm to escort you
to the windward side of the base.

559
00:35:24,664 --> 00:35:27,827
- Thank you.
- I got some camouflage jackets here.

560
00:35:27,900 --> 00:35:31,028
- I suggest you both put them on.
- Camouflage jackets?

561
00:35:31,103 --> 00:35:34,231
Yes, sir. We'll be riding
pretty close to the fence line.

562
00:35:34,306 --> 00:35:36,467
The Cubans see
an officer wearing white...

563
00:35:36,542 --> 00:35:39,102
they think it might be someone
they want to take a shot at.

564
00:35:40,913 --> 00:35:43,381
Good call, Sam.

565
00:35:47,953 --> 00:35:50,581
We'll just hop on the ferry.
We'll be there in no time.

566
00:35:50,656 --> 00:35:53,250
- Wait. We gotta take a boat?
- Yes, sir.

567
00:35:53,325 --> 00:35:56,954
- To get to the other side of the bay.
- Nobody said anything about a boat.

568
00:35:57,029 --> 00:35:59,827
- Is there a problem, sir?
- No, no problem.

569
00:35:59,899 --> 00:36:01,662
Just not crazy about boats.

570
00:36:01,734 --> 00:36:06,000
Jesus Christ, Kaffee,
you're in the Navy, for crying out loud.

571
00:36:06,072 --> 00:36:09,633
- Nobody likes her very much.
- Yes, sir!

572
00:36:22,822 --> 00:36:25,416
Nathan Jessup. Come on in.

573
00:36:25,491 --> 00:36:29,518
Thank you, sir. Daniel Kaffee.
I'm the attorney for Dawson and Downey.

574
00:36:29,595 --> 00:36:31,961
This is
Lieutenant Commander Joanne Galloway.

575
00:36:32,031 --> 00:36:35,228
- Pleasure meeting you, Commander.
- Observing and evaluating, sir.

576
00:36:35,301 --> 00:36:37,235
Lieutenant Sam Weinberg.
He'll be assisting.

577
00:36:37,303 --> 00:36:40,033
- Sir.
- This is my X.O., Colonel Markinson...

578
00:36:40,106 --> 00:36:42,131
and platoon leader Lieutenant Kendrick.

579
00:36:42,208 --> 00:36:44,699
I've asked them to join us.
Sit down, please.

580
00:36:44,777 --> 00:36:47,245
- Lieutenant Kaffee.
- Colonel Markinson.

581
00:36:47,313 --> 00:36:49,804
I had the pleasure
of meeting your father once.

582
00:36:49,882 --> 00:36:51,941
I was a teenager.
He spoke at my high school.

583
00:36:52,952 --> 00:36:54,146
Lionel Kaffee?

584
00:36:54,987 --> 00:36:56,955
- Yes, sir.
- Well, what do you know?

585
00:36:57,022 --> 00:37:01,618
John, this man's dad once made a lot of
enemies down in your neck of the woods.

586
00:37:01,694 --> 00:37:05,460
Jefferson v. Madison County
School District.

587
00:37:05,531 --> 00:37:09,865
Folks down there said a black girl
couldn't go to an all-white school.

588
00:37:09,935 --> 00:37:13,871
Lionel Kaffee said,
"Well, we'll just see about that. "

589
00:37:13,939 --> 00:37:16,499
How the hell is your dad, Danny?

590
00:37:16,575 --> 00:37:18,975
He passed away seven years ago, sir.

591
00:37:20,713 --> 00:37:23,580
Don't I feel like the fuckin' asshole.

592
00:37:23,649 --> 00:37:24,980
Not at all.

593
00:37:26,218 --> 00:37:28,311
Well, what can we do for you, Danny?

594
00:37:28,387 --> 00:37:30,321
Uh, not much, sir.

595
00:37:31,824 --> 00:37:35,726
This is really a formality
more than anything else.

596
00:37:36,796 --> 00:37:39,697
JAG Corps insists that we interview
all the relevant witnesses.

597
00:37:39,765 --> 00:37:41,733
The JAG Corps can be demanding
that way.

598
00:37:43,469 --> 00:37:46,267
John will take you out
and show you what you want to see.

599
00:37:46,338 --> 00:37:48,397
After that we can all
hook up for lunch.

600
00:37:48,474 --> 00:37:51,705
- How does that sound? Good.
- Fine, sir.

601
00:37:59,819 --> 00:38:02,253
I understand you had a meeting
with your men that afternoon.

602
00:38:02,321 --> 00:38:04,653
- Yes, I did.
- What did you guys talk about?

603
00:38:04,723 --> 00:38:07,089
I told the men
that we had an informer among us...

604
00:38:07,159 --> 00:38:10,151
and that despite any desire
they might have to seek retribution...

605
00:38:10,229 --> 00:38:13,721
Private Santiago
was not to be harmed in anyway.

606
00:38:13,799 --> 00:38:17,098
- What time was that meeting?
- 1600.

607
00:38:17,169 --> 00:38:20,036
That's 4:00.

608
00:39:11,390 --> 00:39:13,915
Sam, we should make sure
somebody gets this to his parents.

609
00:39:13,993 --> 00:39:17,156
- We don't need it anymore.
- Right.

610
00:39:18,430 --> 00:39:20,694
Lieutenant Kendrick,
may I call you John?

611
00:39:20,766 --> 00:39:22,825
No, you may not.

612
00:39:22,902 --> 00:39:25,029
Have I done something to offend you?

613
00:39:25,104 --> 00:39:27,197
No, I like all you Navy boys.

614
00:39:27,273 --> 00:39:31,334
Every time we gotta go someplace to
fight, you fellas always give us a ride.

615
00:39:32,711 --> 00:39:36,147
Lieutenant Kendrick,
do you think Santiago was murdered?

616
00:39:36,215 --> 00:39:39,082
Commander, I believe in God
and His Son Jesus Christ.

617
00:39:39,151 --> 00:39:41,142
And because I do, I can say this:

618
00:39:41,220 --> 00:39:44,951
Private Santiago is dead,
and that is a tragedy.

619
00:39:45,024 --> 00:39:47,288
But he is dead
because he had no code.

620
00:39:47,359 --> 00:39:51,659
He is dead because he had no honor,
and God was watching.

621
00:39:54,133 --> 00:39:55,896
How do you feel about that theory?

622
00:39:55,968 --> 00:39:58,198
Sounds good. Let's move on.

623
00:39:58,270 --> 00:40:00,261
Are you planning
on doing any investigating...

624
00:40:00,339 --> 00:40:02,273
or are you just gonna take
the guided tour?

625
00:40:03,909 --> 00:40:06,707
I'm pacing myself.

626
00:40:07,546 --> 00:40:09,275
They were running around
for three hours...

627
00:40:09,348 --> 00:40:12,283
looking for anything white
they could wave in the air.

628
00:40:12,351 --> 00:40:15,650
Some of these people surrendered
to a crew from CNN.

629
00:40:16,722 --> 00:40:21,989
Well, walk softly and carry
an armored tank division, I always say.

630
00:40:23,462 --> 00:40:26,693
- That was delicious. Thank you.
- My pleasure, sir.

631
00:40:26,765 --> 00:40:31,600
Colonel, I do have to ask you a couple
of questions about September 6.

632
00:40:31,670 --> 00:40:33,262
Shoot.

633
00:40:33,339 --> 00:40:35,933
On the morning of the sixth,
you were contacted by an N.I.S. agent...

634
00:40:36,008 --> 00:40:39,444
who said that Santiago tipped him off
to an illegal fence line shooting.

635
00:40:39,511 --> 00:40:41,706
- Yes.
- Santiago would reveal the person...

636
00:40:41,780 --> 00:40:44,578
- in exchange for a transfer.
- Yes.

637
00:40:47,686 --> 00:40:50,484
If you feel there are any details
that I'm missing...

638
00:40:50,556 --> 00:40:53,787
you should feel free to speak up.

639
00:40:56,362 --> 00:40:57,795
Thank you.

640
00:41:01,367 --> 00:41:04,165
Now, at this point you called
Lieutenant Colonel Markinson...

641
00:41:04,236 --> 00:41:06,568
and Lieutenant Kendrick
into your office.

642
00:41:06,638 --> 00:41:08,333
- Is that right?
- Yes.

643
00:41:08,407 --> 00:41:09,567
What happened?

644
00:41:09,641 --> 00:41:15,443
We agreed that, for his own safety,
Santiago should be transferred off base.

645
00:41:15,514 --> 00:41:19,541
Santiago was set to be transferred.

646
00:41:19,618 --> 00:41:22,212
On the first available flight
to the States...

647
00:41:22,287 --> 00:41:24,414
0600 the next morning.

648
00:41:24,490 --> 00:41:28,586
Five hours too late,
as it turned out.

649
00:41:29,862 --> 00:41:31,295
Yeah.

650
00:41:32,865 --> 00:41:35,231
All right. That's all I have.
Thanks very much for your time.

651
00:41:35,300 --> 00:41:38,599
Corporal's waiting with the Jeep.
He'll take you back to the flight line.

652
00:41:38,670 --> 00:41:40,695
- Thank you, sir.
- Wait. I've got some questions.

653
00:41:40,773 --> 00:41:42,400
- No, you don't.
- Yes, I do.

654
00:41:42,474 --> 00:41:45,466
- No, you don't.
- On the morning that Santiago died...

655
00:41:45,544 --> 00:41:49,139
did you meet with Dr. Stone
between 3:00 and 5:00?

656
00:41:49,214 --> 00:41:53,241
Of course I met with the doctor.
One of my men was dead.

657
00:41:53,318 --> 00:41:55,843
See? The man was dead. Let's go.

658
00:41:55,921 --> 00:41:59,584
I'm just wondering if you’ve ever heard
the term "Code Red. "

659
00:42:00,926 --> 00:42:02,621
I've heard the term, yes.

660
00:42:02,694 --> 00:42:05,686
This past February,
you received a cautionary memo...

661
00:42:05,764 --> 00:42:08,062
from the commander-in-chief
of the Atlantic fleet...

662
00:42:08,133 --> 00:42:10,067
warning that the practice
of enlisted men...

663
00:42:10,135 --> 00:42:13,298
disciplining their own
wasn't to be condoned by officers.

664
00:42:13,372 --> 00:42:15,897
Well, I submit to you
that whoever wrote that memo...

665
00:42:15,974 --> 00:42:17,908
has never faced the working end...

666
00:42:17,976 --> 00:42:22,037
of a Soviet-made
Cuban AK-47 assault rifle.

667
00:42:22,114 --> 00:42:25,811
However, the directive
having come from the commander...

668
00:42:25,884 --> 00:42:28,011
I gave it its due attention.

669
00:42:28,087 --> 00:42:30,647
- What is your point, Jo?
- She has no point.

670
00:42:30,722 --> 00:42:32,656
She often has no point.
It's part of her charm.

671
00:42:32,724 --> 00:42:37,718
- We're out of here. Thank you.
- I think Code Reds still go on here.

672
00:42:37,796 --> 00:42:42,062
- Do Code Reds still happen here?
-Jo, he doesn't need to answer that.

673
00:42:42,134 --> 00:42:43,692
- Yes, he does.
- No, he really doesn't.

674
00:42:43,769 --> 00:42:45,828
Yeah, he really does.

675
00:42:50,576 --> 00:42:52,806
You know, it just hit me.

676
00:42:53,879 --> 00:42:55,813
She outranks you, Danny.

677
00:42:55,881 --> 00:42:58,714
- Yes, sir.
- I wanna tell you something.

678
00:42:58,784 --> 00:43:01,309
And listen up,
'cause I really mean this.

679
00:43:01,386 --> 00:43:04,116
You're the luckiest man
in the world.

680
00:43:04,189 --> 00:43:08,489
There is nothing on this earth sexier-
believe me, gentlemen-

681
00:43:08,560 --> 00:43:11,552
than a woman that
you have to salute in the morning.

682
00:43:12,231 --> 00:43:15,530
Promote 'em all, I say,
'cause this is true:

683
00:43:15,601 --> 00:43:18,729
If you haven't gotten a blowjob
from a superior officer...

684
00:43:18,804 --> 00:43:23,264
well, you’re just letting
the best in life pass you by.

685
00:43:24,443 --> 00:43:27,105
Colonel, the practice of Code Reds
is still condoned by officers-

686
00:43:27,179 --> 00:43:31,616
My problem is that I'm a colonel,
so I'll go on taking cold showers...

687
00:43:31,683 --> 00:43:34,243
until they elect some gal president.

688
00:43:34,319 --> 00:43:36,787
I need an answer to my question, sir.

689
00:43:36,855 --> 00:43:40,416
Take caution in your tone, Commander.

690
00:43:40,492 --> 00:43:45,862
I'm a fair guy, but this fucking heat
is making me absolutely crazy.

691
00:43:47,633 --> 00:43:50,067
You wanna ask me about Code Reds?
On the record...

692
00:43:50,135 --> 00:43:52,126
I tell you I discourage
the practice...

693
00:43:52,204 --> 00:43:54,263
in accordance
with the commander's directive.

694
00:43:54,339 --> 00:43:57,365
Off the record,
I tell you it is an invaluable part...

695
00:43:57,442 --> 00:43:59,376
of close-infantry training.

696
00:43:59,444 --> 00:44:03,380
And if it happens to go on
without my knowledge, so be it.

697
00:44:03,448 --> 00:44:06,474
I run my unit how I run my unit.

698
00:44:06,552 --> 00:44:10,989
You wanna investigate me,
roll the dice and take your chances.

699
00:44:11,056 --> 00:44:15,550
I eat breakfast 300 yards from
4,000 Cubans who are trained to kill me.

700
00:44:15,627 --> 00:44:18,721
So don't think for one second that
you can come down here...

701
00:44:18,797 --> 00:44:20,890
flash a badge...

702
00:44:20,966 --> 00:44:23,560
and make me nervous.

703
00:44:27,706 --> 00:44:28,968
Let's go.

704
00:44:31,977 --> 00:44:35,572
Colonel, I'll just need a copy
of Santiago’s transfer order.

705
00:44:36,181 --> 00:44:37,239
What's that?

706
00:44:37,316 --> 00:44:40,444
Santiago's transfer order. You guys
have paperwork on that kind of thing.

707
00:44:40,519 --> 00:44:42,453
I just need it for the file.

708
00:44:42,521 --> 00:44:45,513
- For the file.
- Yeah.

709
00:44:47,659 --> 00:44:51,993
Of course you can have a copy
of the transfer order for the file.

710
00:44:52,064 --> 00:44:55,329
- I'm here to help in anyway I can.
- Thank you.

711
00:44:55,400 --> 00:44:59,427
You believe that, don’t you, Danny, that
I'm here to help you in anyway I can?

712
00:45:00,505 --> 00:45:01,767
Of course.

713
00:45:02,474 --> 00:45:05,966
Corporal will take you by personnel
on your way out to the flight line...

714
00:45:06,044 --> 00:45:10,276
and you can have
all the transfer orders that you want.

715
00:45:11,350 --> 00:45:14,547
- Let's go.
- But you have to ask me nicely.

716
00:45:16,922 --> 00:45:18,184
I beg your pardon?

717
00:45:18,257 --> 00:45:21,385
You have to ask me nicely.

718
00:45:21,460 --> 00:45:24,861
You see, Danny, I can deal with
the bullets and the bombs and the blood.

719
00:45:24,930 --> 00:45:28,093
I don't want money,
and I don't want medals.

720
00:45:28,166 --> 00:45:32,865
What I do want is for you to stand there
in that faggoty white uniform...

721
00:45:32,938 --> 00:45:37,375
and with your Harvard mouth
extend me some fucking courtesy.

722
00:45:40,078 --> 00:45:42,569
You gotta ask me nicely.

723
00:45:46,084 --> 00:45:48,416
Colonel Jessup,
if it’s not too much trouble...

724
00:45:48,487 --> 00:45:52,389
I'd like a copy
of the transfer order, sir.

725
00:45:55,727 --> 00:45:57,160
No problem.

726
00:46:22,220 --> 00:46:25,587
In the seventh. San Diego leads.
Braves try to comeback.

727
00:46:25,657 --> 00:46:27,921
Runners don’t go.

728
00:46:27,993 --> 00:46:30,757
Hard drive, right field.
We're gonna have a tied ballgame.

729
00:46:30,829 --> 00:46:34,788
It's on its way,
and it is now 10 to 10.

730
00:46:34,866 --> 00:46:36,800
And I don't believe it.

731
00:46:40,172 --> 00:46:42,197
- Who is it?
- It's me.

732
00:46:45,010 --> 00:46:49,140
I really missed you. I was just saying
to myself it’s been almost three hours.

733
00:46:49,214 --> 00:46:52,047
- Markinson's disappeared.
- What?

734
00:46:52,117 --> 00:46:54,881
Colonel Markinson's gone U.A.-
unauthorized absence.

735
00:46:54,953 --> 00:46:56,443
I know what it means.
When?

736
00:46:56,521 --> 00:46:58,785
This afternoon.
Sometime after we left.

737
00:46:59,524 --> 00:47:02,152
- I'll try to find him in the morning.
- I've already tried.

738
00:47:02,227 --> 00:47:03,956
You tried?

739
00:47:05,297 --> 00:47:08,630
Joanne, you're coming dangerously close
to the textbook definition...

740
00:47:08,700 --> 00:47:10,998
of interfering
with a government investigation.

741
00:47:11,069 --> 00:47:12,661
I'm Louden Downey's attorney.

742
00:47:13,872 --> 00:47:17,501
Aunt Ginny. She says she feels
like she's known me for years.

743
00:47:17,576 --> 00:47:19,840
So I suggested that she might feel
more comfortable...

744
00:47:19,911 --> 00:47:22,072
if I were directly involved
with the case.

745
00:47:22,147 --> 00:47:25,548
She had Louden sign the papers
about an hour ago.

746
00:47:25,617 --> 00:47:27,585
I suppose
it's way too much to hope...

747
00:47:27,652 --> 00:47:30,120
that you’re making this up
just to bother me.

748
00:47:30,188 --> 00:47:32,349
Don't worry. I'm not gonna
make a motion for separation.

749
00:47:32,424 --> 00:47:35,291
- You're still lead counsel.
- Splendid.

750
00:47:35,360 --> 00:47:38,193
I think Kendrick ordered the Code Red,
and so do you.

751
00:47:40,098 --> 00:47:41,998
Let's go.

752
00:47:45,504 --> 00:47:47,631
Officer on deck!

753
00:47:47,706 --> 00:47:49,640
- Did Kendrick order the Code Red?
- Sir?

754
00:47:49,708 --> 00:47:53,371
Don't say "Sir" like I just asked you
if you cleaned the latrine.

755
00:47:53,445 --> 00:47:55,709
You heard what I said. Did
Lieutenant Kendrick order you guys...

756
00:47:55,781 --> 00:47:57,806
to give Santiago a Code Red?

757
00:47:58,917 --> 00:48:00,214
Yes, sir.

758
00:48:01,753 --> 00:48:03,983
- Did he?
- Yes, sir.

759
00:48:08,960 --> 00:48:12,020
You mind telling me
why you never mentioned this before?

760
00:48:12,097 --> 00:48:16,158
-You didn't ask.
-That won't win you a place in my heart.

761
00:48:16,234 --> 00:48:18,532
I get paid no matter
how much time you spend in jail.

762
00:48:18,603 --> 00:48:20,662
Yes, sir. I know you do, sir.

763
00:48:20,739 --> 00:48:22,900
- Fuck you, Harold!
- All right.

764
00:48:23,942 --> 00:48:26,410
At ease.

765
00:48:26,478 --> 00:48:28,412
- Let's sort this thing out.
- Shit!

766
00:48:28,480 --> 00:48:31,916
There was a platoon meeting
on September 6 at 4:00 in the afternoon.

767
00:48:31,983 --> 00:48:34,349
Lieutenant Kendrick says
that he gave strict instructions...

768
00:48:34,419 --> 00:48:36,512
that nothing was to happen
to Santiago.

769
00:48:36,588 --> 00:48:39,648
Now, is this true?

770
00:48:40,525 --> 00:48:42,356
I want you to speak freely.

771
00:48:45,263 --> 00:48:46,821
Ma'am, that's correct...

772
00:48:46,898 --> 00:48:49,560
but then he dismissed the platoon
and we all went to our rooms.

773
00:48:49,634 --> 00:48:50,999
And what happened then?

774
00:48:51,069 --> 00:48:53,697
Lieutenant Kendrick came
to our room, ma'am.

775
00:48:53,772 --> 00:48:54,830
When?

776
00:48:56,308 --> 00:49:00,540
About five minutes after the meeting
broke, sir. About 1620.

777
00:49:00,612 --> 00:49:02,239
And what happened then?

778
00:49:03,081 --> 00:49:07,575
Lieutenant Kendrick ordered us
to give Santiago a Code Red.

779
00:49:08,954 --> 00:49:10,046
Jack!

780
00:49:10,121 --> 00:49:12,351
Hang on.

781
00:49:12,424 --> 00:49:13,948
They were given an order.

782
00:49:16,862 --> 00:49:19,023
-Jack, come on.
- Be right back.

783
00:49:19,097 --> 00:49:22,294
- What are you doin', Jack?
- Be right back.

784
00:49:22,367 --> 00:49:25,530
- How long did you know about the order?
- I didn't. Who's this?

785
00:49:25,604 --> 00:49:29,267
That's Jo Galloway, Downey's lawyer.
She's very pleased to meet you.

786
00:49:29,341 --> 00:49:32,504
- What exactly are you accusing me of?
- How long did you know about the order?

787
00:49:32,577 --> 00:49:34,602
He didn't, 'cause if he did
and hadn't told us...

788
00:49:34,679 --> 00:49:37,443
he'd be violating about 14 articles
of the Code of Ethics.

789
00:49:37,516 --> 00:49:38,949
He has enough to worry about...

790
00:49:39,017 --> 00:49:41,110
God forbid our clients
decide to plead not guilty...

791
00:49:41,186 --> 00:49:43,416
and testify for the record
that they were given an order.

792
00:49:43,488 --> 00:49:46,116
Kendrick specifically told those men
not to touch Santiago.

793
00:49:46,191 --> 00:49:48,056
That's right. And then he went
into Dawson and Downey's room...

794
00:49:48,126 --> 00:49:50,117
and specifically told them
to give him a Code Red.

795
00:49:50,195 --> 00:49:52,925
- Kendrick said different. Have proof?
- He's lying. I have the defendants.

796
00:49:52,998 --> 00:49:55,125
And I have 23 Marines
who aren't accused of murder...

797
00:49:55,200 --> 00:49:57,498
and a lieutenant
with four letters of commendation.

798
00:49:57,569 --> 00:49:59,764
- Why did Markinson go U.A.?
- We'll never know.

799
00:49:59,838 --> 00:50:02,830
- You don't think I could subpoena him?
- You can try, but you won't find him.

800
00:50:02,908 --> 00:50:06,776
You know what he did for the first 17
of his 26 years in the Corps?

801
00:50:06,845 --> 00:50:11,305
Counterintelligence. Markinson's gone.
There is no Markinson.

802
00:50:12,817 --> 00:50:14,751
Look, Danny.

803
00:50:14,819 --> 00:50:17,344
Jessup's star is on the rise.

804
00:50:17,422 --> 00:50:19,356
Division will give me
a lot of room on this one...

805
00:50:19,424 --> 00:50:21,619
to spare Jessup
and the Corps any embarrassment.

806
00:50:21,693 --> 00:50:22,853
How much?

807
00:50:24,029 --> 00:50:27,590
Involuntary manslaughter,
two years, they're home in six months.

808
00:50:27,666 --> 00:50:29,133
No deal. We're going to court.

809
00:50:29,200 --> 00:50:31,031
- No, you're not.
- Why not?

810
00:50:31,102 --> 00:50:34,401
'Cause you’ll lose,
and Danny knows it.

811
00:50:34,472 --> 00:50:37,202
If we do go to court,
I'm gonna have to go all the way.

812
00:50:37,275 --> 00:50:39,607
They're gonna be charged
with a whole truckload-

813
00:50:39,678 --> 00:50:42,272
murder, conspiracy,
conduct unbecoming.

814
00:50:42,347 --> 00:50:44,747
Even though he's got me by the balls
out here, Danny knows...

815
00:50:44,816 --> 00:50:47,148
that in a courtroom,
he loses this case.

816
00:50:47,218 --> 00:50:49,152
Danny is an awfully talented lawyer.

817
00:50:49,220 --> 00:50:51,620
He's not about to see
his clients go to jail for life...

818
00:50:51,690 --> 00:50:54,181
when he knows
they can be home in six months.

819
00:50:54,926 --> 00:50:56,860
That's the end of this negotiation.

820
00:50:57,762 --> 00:51:00,128
I'll see you tomorrow morning
at the arraignment.

821
00:51:03,535 --> 00:51:06,436
All right. Here's the story.

822
00:51:06,504 --> 00:51:11,203
The government's offering
involuntary manslaughter, two years.

823
00:51:11,276 --> 00:51:13,210
Be home in six months.

824
00:51:15,880 --> 00:51:19,475
Wow, Kaffee!
You're the greatest lawyer in the world!

825
00:51:19,551 --> 00:51:22,611
Ooh, how can we ever thank you?

826
00:51:22,687 --> 00:51:25,247
Fellas, you hear what I just said?

827
00:51:25,323 --> 00:51:28,588
You're going home in six months.

828
00:51:28,660 --> 00:51:30,992
I'm afraid we can't do that, sir.

829
00:51:31,062 --> 00:51:34,395
- Do what?
- Make a deal, sir.

830
00:51:34,466 --> 00:51:35,933
What are you talking about?

831
00:51:36,001 --> 00:51:38,834
We did nothing wrong, sir.
We did our job...

832
00:51:38,903 --> 00:51:42,066
and if that has consequences,
then I'll accept them.

833
00:51:42,140 --> 00:51:44,540
But I won't say that I'm guilty, sir.

834
00:51:45,877 --> 00:51:49,438
Did you-
Did she put you up to this?

835
00:51:49,514 --> 00:51:53,006
- We have a code, sir.
- Oh, well, zip-a-dee-doo-dah!

836
00:51:53,084 --> 00:51:56,417
You and your code plead not guilty.
You'll be in jail the rest of your life.

837
00:51:56,488 --> 00:51:59,548
Do what I'm telling you,
you'll be home in six months.

838
00:52:01,393 --> 00:52:03,361
Do it, Harold.
Six months.

839
00:52:03,428 --> 00:52:05,953
It's nothing.
It's a hockey season.

840
00:52:08,433 --> 00:52:10,128
- Permission to-
- Speak!

841
00:52:10,201 --> 00:52:12,294
Jesus!

842
00:52:14,673 --> 00:52:17,699
- What do we do then, sir?
- When?

843
00:52:17,776 --> 00:52:20,802
After six months, we'll be
dishonorably discharged, right, sir?

844
00:52:20,879 --> 00:52:22,210
Probably.

845
00:52:23,448 --> 00:52:25,439
Well, what do we do then, sir?

846
00:52:28,153 --> 00:52:32,055
We joined the Marines because we wanted
to live our lives by a certain code.

847
00:52:32,123 --> 00:52:33,886
And we found it in the Corps.

848
00:52:33,958 --> 00:52:37,189
Now you’re asking us to sign a piece
of paper that says we have no honor.

849
00:52:37,262 --> 00:52:39,457
You're asking us
to say we’re not Marines.

850
00:52:39,531 --> 00:52:41,829
If a court decides
that what we did was wrong...

851
00:52:41,900 --> 00:52:43,925
then I'll accept
whatever punishment they give.

852
00:52:44,002 --> 00:52:47,460
But I believe I was right, sir.
I believe I did my job...

853
00:52:47,539 --> 00:52:50,872
and I will not dishonor myself,
my unit or the Corps...

854
00:52:50,942 --> 00:52:55,003
so that I can go home
in six months...

855
00:52:55,080 --> 00:52:56,513
sir.

856
00:53:03,722 --> 00:53:08,523
Commander, I'd like to talk to Lance
Corporal Dawson alone for a minute.

857
00:53:10,095 --> 00:53:11,960
Sergeant.

858
00:53:12,030 --> 00:53:14,555
We're gonna go to another room.

859
00:53:14,632 --> 00:53:16,964
- We'd like another holding room.
- All right, ma'am.

860
00:53:17,035 --> 00:53:19,469
- It's gonna be okay.
- Sit down.

861
00:53:30,915 --> 00:53:32,940
You don't like me very much, do you?

862
00:53:34,252 --> 00:53:37,449
Forget it. Don't answer that.
It doesn't matter.

863
00:53:43,661 --> 00:53:45,094
You know...

864
00:53:46,464 --> 00:53:48,398
Downey worships you.

865
00:53:51,136 --> 00:53:53,627
He's gonna do whatever you do.

866
00:53:54,606 --> 00:53:59,407
Are you really gonna let this happen
to him because of a code, Harold?

867
00:53:59,477 --> 00:54:01,911
- Do you think we were right?
- It doesn't matter-

868
00:54:01,980 --> 00:54:06,041
- Do you think we were right?
- I think you’d lose.

869
00:54:08,019 --> 00:54:09,953
You're such a coward.

870
00:54:10,021 --> 00:54:12,581
I can't believe
they let you wear a uniform.

871
00:54:14,959 --> 00:54:17,587
I'm not gonna feel responsible for this.
I did everything I could.

872
00:54:17,662 --> 00:54:20,187
You're going to Leavenworth
for the better part of your life.

873
00:54:20,265 --> 00:54:22,199
And you know what?
I don't give a shit.

874
00:54:24,269 --> 00:54:27,238
What happened to saluting an officer
when he leaves the room?

875
00:54:36,314 --> 00:54:37,406
Open it up.

876
00:54:41,151 --> 00:54:42,948
I don't believe it.

877
00:54:43,019 --> 00:54:45,419
Dawson's gonna go to jail
just to spite me.

878
00:54:45,488 --> 00:54:48,048
Fine. If he wants to jump
off a cliff, that's his business.

879
00:54:48,124 --> 00:54:51,890
I'm not gonna hold his hand on the way.
I wanna get him a new lawyer. How?

880
00:54:51,961 --> 00:54:54,395
Just make a motion tomorrow morning
at the arraignment.

881
00:54:54,464 --> 00:54:56,455
The judge will ask you
if you want to enter a plea...

882
00:54:56,533 --> 00:54:58,933
and you tell him that you want
to have new counsel assigned.

883
00:55:00,470 --> 00:55:01,903
That's that.

884
00:55:01,971 --> 00:55:05,270
One thing, though. When you ask
the judge for new counsel...

885
00:55:05,342 --> 00:55:07,276
Danny, be sure and ask nicely.

886
00:55:08,178 --> 00:55:10,976
- What do you want from me?
- I want you to let them be judged.

887
00:55:11,047 --> 00:55:13,948
I want you to stand up
and make an argument.

888
00:55:14,017 --> 00:55:16,679
An argument that didn't work
for Calley at My Lai.

889
00:55:16,753 --> 00:55:18,880
An argument that didn't work
for the Nazis at Nuremburg.

890
00:55:18,955 --> 00:55:20,889
Oh, for Christ's sake, Sam.

891
00:55:20,957 --> 00:55:23,391
Do you really think that's the same
as two teenage Marines...

892
00:55:23,460 --> 00:55:26,258
executing a routine order they never
believed would result in harm?

893
00:55:26,329 --> 00:55:28,024
These guys aren't the Nazis.

894
00:55:28,098 --> 00:55:31,158
Don't look now, Danny,
but you’re making an argument.

895
00:55:32,769 --> 00:55:36,296
Yeah, yeah. Tomorrow morning
I get them a new attorney.

896
00:55:36,373 --> 00:55:38,341
Why are you so afraid
to be a lawyer?

897
00:55:38,408 --> 00:55:40,876
Were Daddy's expectations
really that high?

898
00:55:40,944 --> 00:55:44,539
Oh, please. Spare me
the psycho-babble father bullshit!

899
00:55:44,614 --> 00:55:48,015
Dawson and Downey will have their day
in court, but with another lawyer.

900
00:55:48,084 --> 00:55:51,053
Another lawyer won’t be good enough.
They need you.

901
00:55:51,121 --> 00:55:54,682
You know how to win. You know they have
a case, and you know how to win.

902
00:55:54,758 --> 00:55:57,192
If you walk away from this now,
you've sealed their fate.

903
00:55:57,260 --> 00:56:00,627
Their fate was sealed
the moment Santiago died.

904
00:56:00,697 --> 00:56:03,325
- Do you believe they have a case?
- You and Dawson.

905
00:56:03,400 --> 00:56:05,459
You both live
in the same dream world.

906
00:56:05,535 --> 00:56:07,469
It doesn't matter what I believe.

907
00:56:07,537 --> 00:56:09,664
It only matters what I can prove.

908
00:56:09,739 --> 00:56:12,674
So, please, don't tell me
what I know and don't know!

909
00:56:12,742 --> 00:56:14,505
I know the law!

910
00:56:19,482 --> 00:56:21,416
You know nothing about the law.

911
00:56:21,484 --> 00:56:23,679
You're a used car salesman, Daniel.

912
00:56:23,753 --> 00:56:26,244
You're an ambulance chaser
with a rank.

913
00:56:26,322 --> 00:56:29,416
You're nothing. Live with that.

914
00:56:35,965 --> 00:56:37,899
So I told Duncan...

915
00:56:37,967 --> 00:56:42,131
"If you wanna take this to court
I'm gonna file nine discovery motions...

916
00:56:42,205 --> 00:56:45,504
and you're gonna spend a year
going blind on paperwork...

917
00:56:45,575 --> 00:56:49,067
because a 90-year-old man
misread the Delaware insurance code. "

918
00:56:49,145 --> 00:56:51,340
- So what happened?
- He calls back 15 minutes later.

919
00:56:51,414 --> 00:56:53,348
He says, " Let's make a deal. "

920
00:57:40,530 --> 00:57:41,963
All rise.

921
00:57:49,472 --> 00:57:50,564
Where are we?

922
00:57:52,242 --> 00:57:55,803
Docket number 411275VR-5.

923
00:57:55,879 --> 00:57:58,905
The United States v.
Lance Corporal Harold W. Dawson...

924
00:57:58,982 --> 00:58:01,007
and Private First Class Louden Downey.

925
00:58:01,084 --> 00:58:04,212
The accused are charged with murder,
conspiracy to commit murder...

926
00:58:04,287 --> 00:58:06,847
and conduct unbecoming
a United States Marine.

927
00:58:06,923 --> 00:58:09,118
Does the defense wish to enter a plea?

928
00:58:10,894 --> 00:58:12,327
Yeah.

929
00:58:16,032 --> 00:58:17,431
They're not guilty.

930
00:58:20,603 --> 00:58:23,197
Enter a plea of not guilty
for the accused.

931
00:58:23,273 --> 00:58:26,538
We'll adjourn until 1000,
three weeks from today...

932
00:58:26,609 --> 00:58:29,544
at which time this general
court-martial will reconvene.

933
00:58:46,129 --> 00:58:49,587
Why does a lieutenant junior grade
with ninth months' experience...

934
00:58:49,666 --> 00:58:53,033
and a track record for plea bargaining
get assigned a murder case?

935
00:58:55,872 --> 00:58:58,864
Would it be so that it never sees
the inside of a courtroom?

936
00:59:01,477 --> 00:59:03,411
We'll work out of my apartment
every night, 7:00.

937
00:59:03,479 --> 00:59:08,109
Jo, pick up a carton of legal pads, half
a dozen boxes of red and black pens.

938
00:59:08,184 --> 00:59:11,415
Sam, get a couple of desk lamps.
I need a preliminary medical profile.

939
00:59:11,487 --> 00:59:15,924
Jo, we need all proficiency and conduct
reports on Dawson, Downey and Santiago.

940
00:59:15,992 --> 00:59:18,187
The only thing I have to eat
is Yoo-hoo and Cocoa Puffs...

941
00:59:18,261 --> 00:59:20,195
so if you want anything else,
bring it with you.

942
00:59:20,263 --> 00:59:22,424
- Okay?
- Yeah.

943
00:59:28,504 --> 00:59:30,904
So this is what
a courtroom looks like.

944
00:59:41,384 --> 00:59:43,909
Were you able to speak
to your friend at the N.I.S.?

945
00:59:44,988 --> 00:59:48,253
Yeah. She said if Markinson
doesn't want to be found...

946
00:59:48,324 --> 00:59:50,224
we're not gonna find him.

947
00:59:50,293 --> 00:59:53,228
She said I could be Markinson,
and you wouldn't know it.

948
00:59:54,797 --> 00:59:56,356
Are you Markinson?

949
00:59:57,257 --> 00:59:58,357
No.

950
00:59:59,135 --> 01:00:01,035
I'm not Markinson.

951
01:00:02,138 --> 01:00:04,299
That's two down.

952
01:00:06,109 --> 01:00:07,303
What?

953
01:00:09,479 --> 01:00:12,778
I'm just wondering,
now that Joanne’s on this-

954
01:00:12,849 --> 01:00:15,374
I'm just wondering
if you still need me.

955
01:00:15,451 --> 01:00:18,249
- They were following orders.
- An illegal order.

956
01:00:18,321 --> 01:00:20,551
Do you think they knew
it was an illegal order?

957
01:00:20,623 --> 01:00:23,956
It doesn't matter what they knew.
Any decent human being would have refused-

958
01:00:24,027 --> 01:00:26,291
They're not permitted
to question orders.

959
01:00:26,362 --> 01:00:29,388
Then what's the secret? Huh?
What are the magic words?

960
01:00:29,465 --> 01:00:31,057
I give orders every day-

961
01:00:31,134 --> 01:00:33,068
We have softball games
and marching bands.

962
01:00:33,136 --> 01:00:37,334
They work at a place where you have to
wear camouflage or you might get shot!

963
01:00:45,081 --> 01:00:47,140
I need you.

964
01:00:47,216 --> 01:00:52,153
You're better at research than I am,
and you know how to prepare a witness.

965
01:00:57,560 --> 01:01:00,688
I've got medical reports
and Chinese food. I say we eat first.

966
01:01:08,204 --> 01:01:09,262
What?

967
01:01:11,474 --> 01:01:13,408
You got any kung pao chicken?

968
01:01:16,779 --> 01:01:20,306
This is our defense- intent. No one
can prove there was poison on the rag.

969
01:01:20,383 --> 01:01:23,250
Code Red- they're common
and accepted in Guantanamo Bay.

970
01:01:23,319 --> 01:01:27,688
The order- A: Kendrick gave it,
B: They had to follow it.

971
01:01:27,757 --> 01:01:29,884
- That's it.
- What about motive?

972
01:01:29,959 --> 01:01:31,984
We're a little weak on motive.
They had one.

973
01:01:32,061 --> 01:01:34,222
- Just because a person has a motive
doesn't mean they're guilty. - Relax.

974
01:01:34,297 --> 01:01:36,663
We'll deal with the fence line shooting
when it comes up.

975
01:01:36,733 --> 01:01:39,896
Let's start with intent. I don't
want to know what made Santiago die.

976
01:01:39,969 --> 01:01:42,904
I just want to show it could've been
something other than poison.

977
01:01:42,972 --> 01:01:46,533
Jo, talk to doctors. Find out everything
there is to know about lactic acidosis.

978
01:01:46,609 --> 01:01:49,908
This is Lieutenant Commander Galloway
with the JAG Corps in Washington.

979
01:01:49,979 --> 01:01:53,210
I've been trying to track down
a Lieutenant Colonel Matthew Markinson.

980
01:01:53,282 --> 01:01:56,115
Doctor, was there any sign
of external damage?

981
01:01:56,185 --> 01:02:00,679
No scrapes? No cuts?
Bruises? Broken bones?

982
01:02:00,757 --> 01:02:05,126
- Was there any sign of violence?
- You mean, other than the dead body?

983
01:02:05,194 --> 01:02:07,958
Shit, I walk into that
every goddamn time.

984
01:02:08,030 --> 01:02:12,660
He ordered me and Lance Corporal Dawson
to give Willie a Code Red.

985
01:02:12,735 --> 01:02:14,965
Answers still have to come
much faster.

986
01:02:15,037 --> 01:02:17,130
This Iowa farm boy thing
will play for a while...

987
01:02:17,206 --> 01:02:19,606
but in the end, it sounds
like he's searching for the truth.

988
01:02:19,675 --> 01:02:21,939
He's right. From now on,
Willie is Private Santiago.

989
01:02:22,011 --> 01:02:24,343
You start calling him Willie,
and all of a sudden he's a person...

990
01:02:24,413 --> 01:02:26,643
who's got a mother
who's gonna miss him, okay?

991
01:02:26,716 --> 01:02:28,650
They drew the court members
this afternoon.

992
01:02:28,718 --> 01:02:31,016
Seven men, two women,
five Navy, four Marines.

993
01:02:31,087 --> 01:02:33,612
All officers with line experience.
Neither of the women have children.

994
01:02:33,689 --> 01:02:35,987
That's a bad break.
There’s nothing we can do.

995
01:02:36,058 --> 01:02:38,822
My father always said a jury trial
is not just about the law.

996
01:02:38,895 --> 01:02:42,058
It's about assigning blame.
Santiago's dead, and he shouldn't be.

997
01:02:42,131 --> 01:02:44,998
These nine people are gonna insist
that someone be blamed for that.

998
01:02:45,067 --> 01:02:47,535
Ross is handing them our clients.
We're gonna hand them Kendrick.

999
01:02:47,603 --> 01:02:51,130
This is about a sales pitch. It's not going to be won
by the law. It's gonna be won by the lawyers.

1000
01:02:51,207 --> 01:02:54,506
So remember, poker faces. Don’t flinch
in front of the court members.

1001
01:02:54,577 --> 01:02:58,343
Something doesn't go our way, don't hang
your head or shift in your seat.

1002
01:02:58,414 --> 01:03:02,145
Whatever happens, you have to look like
it's exactly what you knew would happen.

1003
01:03:02,218 --> 01:03:06,814
- If you pass me documents-
- Do it swiftly and don't look eager.

1004
01:03:06,889 --> 01:03:10,154
Don't wear that perfume in court.
Wrecks my concentration.

1005
01:03:10,226 --> 01:03:11,659
Really?

1006
01:03:11,727 --> 01:03:14,059
I was talking to Sam.

1007
01:03:15,431 --> 01:03:16,830
What time is it?

1008
01:03:16,899 --> 01:03:18,890
It's time to go home.
Try to get some sleep tonight.

1009
01:03:18,968 --> 01:03:20,993
- Yeah.
- Give me a ride?

1010
01:03:21,070 --> 01:03:22,503
Sure.

1011
01:03:25,474 --> 01:03:27,635
You're a good man, Charlie Brown.

1012
01:03:27,710 --> 01:03:30,201
I'll see you in court, counselor.

1013
01:03:36,953 --> 01:03:39,148
- Danny, I-
- You don't have to say it.

1014
01:03:39,222 --> 01:03:41,622
We've had our differences.
I said some things I didn't mean.

1015
01:03:41,691 --> 01:03:45,058
You said some things you didn't mean,
but you’re happy I stuck with the case.

1016
01:03:45,127 --> 01:03:49,530
And if you’ve gained a certain respect
for me over the last three weeks...

1017
01:03:49,599 --> 01:03:51,658
of course, I'm happy about that.

1018
01:03:51,734 --> 01:03:53,827
But we don't have to make
a whole big deal out of it.

1019
01:03:53,903 --> 01:03:56,167
If you like me,
I won't make you say it.

1020
01:03:56,239 --> 01:03:59,675
I was just gonna tell you
to wear matching socks tomorrow.

1021
01:04:01,544 --> 01:04:04,877
Okay. Good tip.

1022
01:04:05,715 --> 01:04:06,977
We're ready.

1023
01:04:07,049 --> 01:04:09,483
Better believe it.

1024
01:04:19,395 --> 01:04:21,329
We're gonna get creamed.

1025
01:04:50,793 --> 01:04:52,920
- Lieutenant Kaffee?
- Yes?

1026
01:04:52,995 --> 01:04:55,361
You are gonna save our son,
aren’t you?

1027
01:04:56,432 --> 01:04:57,763
I'll do my best.

1028
01:04:58,534 --> 01:05:03,198
Danny, I'd like you to meet
Ginny Miller, Louden's aunt.

1029
01:05:04,206 --> 01:05:07,175
- You're Aunt Ginny?
- Uh-huh.

1030
01:05:08,377 --> 01:05:11,540
I'm sorry. I was expecting
someone older.

1031
01:05:11,614 --> 01:05:13,343
So was I.

1032
01:05:17,420 --> 01:05:19,445
Last chance.
I'll flip you for it.

1033
01:05:19,522 --> 01:05:21,956
- All rise.
- Too late.

1034
01:05:30,466 --> 01:05:33,629
All those having business
with this general court-martial...

1035
01:05:33,703 --> 01:05:36,263
stand forward
and you shall be heard.

1036
01:05:36,339 --> 01:05:39,797
Colonel Julius Alexander Randolph
is presiding.

1037
01:05:39,875 --> 01:05:42,435
Is the government prepared
to make an opening statement?

1038
01:05:42,511 --> 01:05:43,944
Yes, sir.

1039
01:05:47,249 --> 01:05:49,308
The facts of the case are these:

1040
01:05:49,385 --> 01:05:52,183
On midnight of September 6,
the accused entered the barracks room...

1041
01:05:52,254 --> 01:05:55,223
of their platoon mate,
P.F.C. William Santiago.

1042
01:05:55,291 --> 01:05:58,385
They woke him up,
tied his arms and legs with tape...

1043
01:05:58,461 --> 01:06:00,725
and forced a rag into his throat.

1044
01:06:00,796 --> 01:06:04,391
A few minutes later, a chemical reaction
called lactic acidosis...

1045
01:06:04,467 --> 01:06:06,594
caused his lungs to begin bleeding.

1046
01:06:06,669 --> 01:06:08,603
He drowned in his own blood...

1047
01:06:08,671 --> 01:06:12,300
and was pronounced dead
at 37 minutes past midnight.

1048
01:06:12,375 --> 01:06:17,403
These are the facts of the case,
and they are undisputed.

1049
01:06:17,480 --> 01:06:21,109
That's right.
The story I’ve just told you...

1050
01:06:21,183 --> 01:06:24,744
is the exact same story you’re gonna
hear from Lance Corporal Dawson...

1051
01:06:24,820 --> 01:06:27,550
and it's the exact same story
you're gonna hear from Private Downey.

1052
01:06:27,623 --> 01:06:30,319
Furthermore, the government
will also demonstrate...

1053
01:06:30,393 --> 01:06:32,827
that the accused
soaked the rag in poison...

1054
01:06:32,895 --> 01:06:36,991
and entered Santiago's room
with motive and intent to kill.

1055
01:06:38,401 --> 01:06:40,426
Now, Lieutenant Kaffee...

1056
01:06:40,503 --> 01:06:43,597
is gonna try and pull off
a little magic act here.

1057
01:06:43,672 --> 01:06:46,163
He's gonna try a little misdirection.

1058
01:06:46,242 --> 01:06:49,973
He's gonna astonish you
with stories of rituals...

1059
01:06:50,046 --> 01:06:52,947
and dazzle you
with official-sounding terms...

1060
01:06:53,015 --> 01:06:54,949
like "Code Red. "

1061
01:06:56,118 --> 01:06:59,349
He might even try to cut into
a few officers for you.

1062
01:06:59,422 --> 01:07:04,291
He'll have no evidence, mind you, none,
but it's gonna be entertaining.

1063
01:07:04,360 --> 01:07:07,852
And when we get to the end,
all the magic in the world...

1064
01:07:07,930 --> 01:07:10,626
will not have been able to divert
your attention from the fact...

1065
01:07:10,699 --> 01:07:16,194
that Willie Santiago is dead
and Dawson and Downey killed him.

1066
01:07:17,740 --> 01:07:21,232
These are the facts of the case,
and they are undisputed.

1067
01:07:23,045 --> 01:07:24,637
Lieutenant Kaffee.

1068
01:07:24,713 --> 01:07:27,614
There was no poison on the rag,
and there was no intent to kill.

1069
01:07:27,683 --> 01:07:32,416
Any attempt to prove otherwise is futile
'cause it just ain't true.

1070
01:07:32,488 --> 01:07:35,719
When Dawson and Downey went
into Santiago's room that night...

1071
01:07:35,791 --> 01:07:38,385
it wasn't because of vengeance
or hatred.

1072
01:07:38,461 --> 01:07:42,158
It wasn't to kill or harm, and it wasn't
because they were looking for kicks.

1073
01:07:42,231 --> 01:07:44,961
It's because it was
what they were ordered to do.

1074
01:07:46,368 --> 01:07:47,801
Let me say that again.

1075
01:07:47,870 --> 01:07:50,930
It's because it was
what they were ordered to do.

1076
01:07:51,907 --> 01:07:53,602
Out in the real world
that means nothing...

1077
01:07:53,676 --> 01:07:57,840
and here at the Washington Navy Yard
it doesn't mean a whole lot more.

1078
01:07:57,913 --> 01:08:01,872
But if you’re a Marine assigned
to Rifle Security Company Windward...

1079
01:08:01,951 --> 01:08:04,886
Guantanamo Bay, Cuba,
and you're given an order...

1080
01:08:04,954 --> 01:08:07,548
you follow it
or you pack your bags.

1081
01:08:07,623 --> 01:08:09,614
Make no mistake about it.

1082
01:08:09,692 --> 01:08:12,957
Harold Dawson and Louden Downey
are sitting before you today...

1083
01:08:13,028 --> 01:08:16,395
because they did their job.

1084
01:08:19,902 --> 01:08:22,200
Is the government ready
to call its first witness?

1085
01:08:23,339 --> 01:08:26,934
If it please the court,
the government calls Mr. R.C. McGuire.

1086
01:08:31,380 --> 01:08:33,575
Mr. McGuire, would you
raise your right hand, please?

1087
01:08:33,649 --> 01:08:36,413
Do you solemnly swear that the testimony
you give this general court-martial...

1088
01:08:36,485 --> 01:08:39,420
will be the truth, the whole truth
and nothing but the truth?

1089
01:08:39,488 --> 01:08:42,821
- I do.
- Have a seat, please, sir.

1090
01:08:42,892 --> 01:08:46,259
Would you state your full name
and occupation, for the record?

1091
01:08:46,328 --> 01:08:50,765
Robert C. McGuire, Special Agent,
Naval Investigative Service.

1092
01:08:50,833 --> 01:08:55,133
Mr. McGuire, did your office receive
a letter from P.F.C. William Santiago...

1093
01:08:55,204 --> 01:08:57,331
on 3 September of this year?

1094
01:08:57,406 --> 01:08:59,704
- We did.
- What did that letter say?

1095
01:08:59,775 --> 01:09:04,439
That a member of Santiago’s unit had
illegally fired his weapon over the fence line.

1096
01:09:04,513 --> 01:09:06,640
Was that Marine
identified in the letter?

1097
01:09:06,715 --> 01:09:10,242
No. I notified the barracks C.O.
Colonel Jessup...

1098
01:09:10,319 --> 01:09:12,344
that I would be coming down
to investigate.

1099
01:09:12,421 --> 01:09:14,150
And what did you find?

1100
01:09:14,223 --> 01:09:17,283
The shift reported only one sentry
returned his weapon to the switch...

1101
01:09:17,359 --> 01:09:19,350
with a round of ammunition missing.

1102
01:09:19,428 --> 01:09:22,659
- Who was that?
- Lance Corporal Harold Dawson.

1103
01:09:22,731 --> 01:09:24,323
Your witness.

1104
01:09:27,002 --> 01:09:30,233
Mr. McGuire, have you questioned Dawson
about the fence line shooting?

1105
01:09:30,306 --> 01:09:34,265
Yes. He claims to have been engaged
in some manner by the enemy.

1106
01:09:34,343 --> 01:09:36,538
- You don' believe him?
- It's not my place-

1107
01:09:36,612 --> 01:09:38,842
Lance Corporal Dawson's been charged
with a number of crimes.

1108
01:09:38,914 --> 01:09:41,576
Why wasn’t he charged with firing
at the enemy without cause?

1109
01:09:43,352 --> 01:09:46,253
There wasn't enough evidence
to support such a charge.

1110
01:09:46,322 --> 01:09:48,256
Thank you.

1111
01:09:49,325 --> 01:09:51,452
Mr. McGuire, I don't understand
what you mean when you say...

1112
01:09:51,527 --> 01:09:54,121
"There wasn't enough evidence
to support such a charge. "

1113
01:09:54,196 --> 01:09:56,494
You had William Santiago's letter.

1114
01:09:57,766 --> 01:09:59,700
Santiago was the only eyewitness.

1115
01:09:59,768 --> 01:10:03,204
I never had the chance to interview him,
so I don't know what he saw.

1116
01:10:03,272 --> 01:10:06,332
And now we'll never know,
will we, Mr. McGuire?

1117
01:10:10,045 --> 01:10:12,980
- No more questions.
- The witness is excused.

1118
01:10:17,019 --> 01:10:19,715
Corporal Carl Edward Hammaker,
Marine Barracks...

1119
01:10:19,788 --> 01:10:23,053
Rifle Security Company Windward,
Second Platoon Bravo.

1120
01:10:23,125 --> 01:10:26,561
Corporal, were you present at a meeting
that Lieutenant Kendrick held...

1121
01:10:26,629 --> 01:10:29,996
on the afternoon of September 6
with the members of the Second Platoon?

1122
01:10:30,065 --> 01:10:31,362
Yes, sir.

1123
01:10:31,433 --> 01:10:34,027
Would you tell the court
the substance of that meeting?

1124
01:10:34,103 --> 01:10:37,266
Lieutenant Kendrick told us
we had an informer in our group-

1125
01:10:37,339 --> 01:10:40,035
that Private Santiago had gone
outside the chain of command...

1126
01:10:40,109 --> 01:10:43,044
and reported to the N.I.S.
on a member of our platoon.

1127
01:10:43,112 --> 01:10:47,014
Did that make you mad?
You can tell the truth, Corporal.

1128
01:10:47,082 --> 01:10:48,913
- Did it make you mad?
- Yes, sir.

1129
01:10:48,984 --> 01:10:50,212
How mad?

1130
01:10:50,286 --> 01:10:54,120
Private Santiago betrayed a code
we believe in very deeply, sir.

1131
01:10:54,189 --> 01:10:57,181
- Were the other squad members angry?
- Object. Speculation.

1132
01:10:57,259 --> 01:10:59,454
- Were Dawson and Downey?
- Is the government counsel...

1133
01:10:59,528 --> 01:11:04,090
honestly asking the witness to testify
as to how my clients felt?

1134
01:11:04,166 --> 01:11:06,100
Sustained.

1135
01:11:07,936 --> 01:11:11,895
Corporal, did Lieutenant Kendrick
leave a standing order at that meeting?

1136
01:11:11,974 --> 01:11:14,067
- Yes, sir.
- What was it?

1137
01:11:15,844 --> 01:11:19,871
Well, it was clear that he didn't want
us taking matters into our own hands.

1138
01:11:19,948 --> 01:11:21,939
What was the order?

1139
01:11:23,819 --> 01:11:26,788
Sir, he said Santiago
wasn't to be touched.

1140
01:11:28,357 --> 01:11:29,949
Your witness.

1141
01:11:31,026 --> 01:11:33,017
Corporal Hammaker, were you
in Dawson and Downey's barracks...

1142
01:11:33,095 --> 01:11:34,926
five minutes after this meeting?

1143
01:11:34,997 --> 01:11:36,555
No, sir.

1144
01:11:36,632 --> 01:11:39,294
Thanks.
I have no more questions.

1145
01:11:39,368 --> 01:11:41,427
The witness is excused.

1146
01:11:45,274 --> 01:11:47,572
The government calls
Corporal Raymond Thomas.

1147
01:11:47,643 --> 01:11:50,874
I understand Captain Ross is planning
on calling all the other members...

1148
01:11:50,946 --> 01:11:53,574
of Rifle Security Company Windward
to testify.

1149
01:11:53,649 --> 01:11:55,844
In light of the defense Lieutenant
Kaffee is planning to mount...

1150
01:11:55,918 --> 01:11:59,854
the explicit instructions of a platoon
leader seems particularly relevant.

1151
01:11:59,922 --> 01:12:02,447
The defense is willing to concede
that all 22 witnesses...

1152
01:12:02,524 --> 01:12:04,822
will testify substantially
as Corporal Hammaker did...

1153
01:12:04,893 --> 01:12:07,259
if the government is willing to concede
that none of them...

1154
01:12:07,329 --> 01:12:10,958
were in Dawson and Downey's room
at 16:20 on September 6.

1155
01:12:11,033 --> 01:12:12,967
Captain?

1156
01:12:13,035 --> 01:12:15,503
The government will stipulate.

1157
01:12:15,571 --> 01:12:19,530
Then we'll adjourn for the day.
You can call your next witness tomorrow.

1158
01:12:19,608 --> 01:12:21,542
All rise.

1159
01:12:33,021 --> 01:12:34,955
I want to go over the doctor again.

1160
01:12:35,023 --> 01:12:37,890
- We're taking the right approach.
- We've been over this already.

1161
01:12:37,960 --> 01:12:41,555
Listen to me. 3:00- Stone says
he doesn't know what killed Santiago.

1162
01:12:41,630 --> 01:12:45,327
Then he meets with Jessup,
and at 5:00 he says it was poison?

1163
01:12:45,401 --> 01:12:48,131
- The doctor's not telling the truth.
- Oh, that's a relief!.

1164
01:12:48,203 --> 01:12:51,297
